{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1781519200136,"sessionID":"ses_1352f6392ffeYuDqFBXc7h0kg7","part":{"id":"prt_ecad1af82001Fje81d5S0G3tHv","messageID":"msg_ecad1ab0f001QoOWF6H7I0F0mt","sessionID":"ses_1352f6392ffeYuDqFBXc7h0kg7","snapshot":"88ac99a8c45728217066565684cf6c766f2b0303","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1781519203958,"sessionID":"ses_1352f6392ffeYuDqFBXc7h0kg7","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_00_4bVjN6hDIk97dPDIH8R09148","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/149-operate-like-fable-5/002-fable-mode-efficiency-research/research/lineages/codex-xhigh/recommendations.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/149-operate-like-fable-5/002-fable-mode-efficiency-research/research/lineages/codex-xhigh/recommendations.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Recommendations: codex-xhigh Fable-5 Efficiency Map\n2: \n3: ## Verdict\n4: Do not spend round 2 on another AGENTS-style doctrine dump. Round 1 already landed the core doctrine. Spend the next implementation packet on persistent mechanism plus measurement:\n5: \n6: 1. compact Fable governor via prompt-time hook/advisor bridge;\n7: 2. leak-test-style measurement route;\n8: 3. executor provenance fail-loud hardening.\n9: \n10: ## Ranked Items\n11: | Rank | Tier | Surface | Delta | Why it wins | Dedup status |\n12: |---:|---|---|---|---|---|\n13: | 1 | B | Skill Advisor prompt-time hook / OpenCode bridge / Codex UserPromptSubmit | Inject compact Fable governor capsule every prompt when enabled | Matches source thermostat pattern and has highest runtime reach | New |\n14: | 2 | C | `/doctor fable-mode` or `/deep:*benchmark` | Report median words/message, tool:text, caveat %, self-opener %, and evidence-backed completion ratio | Makes behavior measurable instead of aesthetic | New |\n15: | 3 | B | deep-loop-runtime executor audit | Fail loud on CLI crash, model mismatch, or fallback; record actual process provenance | Prevents false research claims and repeats prior defect | Carries prior defect |\n16: | 4 | B | sk-code / sk-code-review | Add blast-radius-gated mutation-check guidance | Pins tests and claims to observable failure | New ritual |\n17: | 5 | B | memory save / handover templates | Add scar-tissue trap ledger with blast site and activation condition | Keeps cold-successor handoffs from rotting | New ritual |\n18: | 6 | A | governor capsule or global voice | Add minimal recursion-control/outcome-over-visible-process text | Useful only if kept short | Partly new |\n19: | 7 | B | orchestrate / deep-review / agent I/O | Strengthen claim/verdict/evidence and contradiction adjudication | Extends finding-as-hypothesis to child outputs | Partly covered |\n20: | 8 | C | deep benchmark family | Fixture-based governor evaluation | Alternative or complement to doctor route | New |\n21: \n22: ## Suggested Sequence\n23: 1. Land rank 3 first if more fan-out research will run; otherwise provenance can keep lying.\n24: 2. Land rank 1 and rank 2 together: governor plus measurement.\n25: 3. Add rank 4 and rank 5 as targeted ritual upgrades.\n26: 4. Only then consider rank 6/7 text, and keep it compact.\n27: \n28: ## Governor Capsule Candidate\n29: Reason about the problem and the person, not model self-image. One self-audit maximum, then return to the task. Qualify only when the qualifier changes what the reader should do. Make reversible decisions and move. Batch tool work; report at natural checkpoints. Open with the result or object, not self-narration. Preserve depth aimed at the problem.\n30: \n31: ## Measurement Candidate\n32: | Metric | Source | Direction |\n33: |---|---|---|\n34: | Median words/message | `leak_test.py` | lower toward Fable, but not at the expense of task success |\n35: | Tool:text ratio | `leak_test.py` | higher in execution work |\n36: | Unsolicited caveat % | `leak_test.py` | lower |\n37: | Self-opener % | `leak_test.py` | lower |\n38: | Evidence-backed completion ratio | Public-specific extension | higher |\n39: \n40: ## Do Not Do\n41: | Avoid | Reason |\n42: |---|---|\n43: | Another long AGENTS block | Round 1 already used that channel and the profile warns about doc sprawl |\n44: | Slash-command-only mode | Too opt-in and local |\n45: | Capability-equivalence claims | Source says prompts cannot change weights |\n46: | Silent executor fallback | Directly contradicts the Fable \"artifact must not lie\" doctrine |\n47: \n48: ## Evidence Anchors\n49: - Round-2 scope: `.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/149-operate-like-fable-5/002-fable-mode-efficiency-research/spec.md:77`\n50: - Round-1 shipped set: `.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/149-operate-like-fable-5/001-initial-refinement/before-vs-after.md:17`\n51: - Governor source: `.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/149-operate-like-fable-5/external/opus-fable-mode-main/governor-block.md:4`\n52: - Re-injection source: `.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/149-operate-like-fable-5/external/opus-fable-mode-main/reinject.sh:4`\n53: - Metric source: `.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/149-operate-like-fable-5/external/opus-fable-mode-main/leak_test.py:13`\n54: - Hook surface: `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/references/hooks/skill_advisor_hook.md:36`\n55: - Self-invocation caveat: `.opencode/skills/cli-codex/SKILL.md:17`\n\n(End of file - total 55 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Recommendations: codex-xhigh Fable-5 Efficiency Map\n\n## Verdict\nDo not spend round 2 on another AGENTS-style doctrine dump. Round 1 already landed the core doctrine. Spend the next implementation packet on persistent mechanism plus measurement:\n\n1. compact Fable governor via prompt-time hook/advisor bridge;\n2. leak-test-style measurement route;\n3. executor provenance fail-loud hardening.\n\n## Ranked Items\n| Rank | Tier | Surface | Delta | Why it wins | Dedup status |\n|---:|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | B | Skill Advisor prompt-time hook / OpenCode bridge / Codex UserPromptSubmit | Inject compact Fable governor capsule every prompt when enabled | Matches source thermostat pattern and has highest runtime reach | New |\n| 2 | C | `/doctor fable-mode` or `/deep:*benchmark` | Report median words/message, tool:text, caveat %, self-opener %, and evidence-backed completion ratio | Makes behavior measurable instead of aesthetic | New |\n| 3 | B | deep-loop-runtime executor audit | Fail loud on CLI crash, model mismatch, or fallback; record actual process provenance | Prevents false research claims and repeats prior defect | Carries prior defect |\n| 4 | B | sk-code / sk-code-review | Add blast-radius-gated mutation-check guidance | Pins tests and claims to observable failure | New ritual |\n| 5 | B | memory save / handover templates | Add scar-tissue trap ledger with blast site and activation condition | Keeps cold-successor handoffs from rotting | New ritual |\n| 6 | A | governor capsule or global voice | Add minimal recursion-control/outcome-over-visible-process text | Useful only if kept short | Partly new |\n| 7 | B | orchestrate / deep-review / agent I/O | Strengthen claim/verdict/evidence and contradiction adjudication | Extends finding-as-hypothesis to child outputs | Partly covered |\n| 8 | C | deep benchmark family | Fixture-based governor evaluation | Alternative or complement to doctor route | New |","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/149-operate-like-fable-5/002-fable-mode-efficiency-research/research/lineages/codex-xhigh/recommendations.md","text":"# Recommendations: codex-xhigh Fable-5 Efficiency Map\n\n## Verdict\nDo not spend round 2 on another AGENTS-style doctrine dump. Round 1 already landed the core doctrine. Spend the next implementation packet on persistent mechanism plus measurement:\n\n1. compact Fable governor via prompt-time hook/advisor bridge;\n2. leak-test-style measurement route;\n3. executor provenance fail-loud hardening.\n\n## Ranked Items\n| Rank | Tier | Surface | Delta | Why it wins | Dedup status |\n|---:|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | B | Skill Advisor prompt-time hook / OpenCode bridge / Codex UserPromptSubmit | Inject compact Fable governor capsule every prompt when enabled | Matches source thermostat pattern and has highest runtime reach | New |\n| 2 | C | `/doctor fable-mode` or `/deep:*benchmark` | Report median words/message, tool:text, caveat %, self-opener %, and evidence-backed completion ratio | Makes behavior measurable instead of aesthetic | New |\n| 3 | B | deep-loop-runtime executor audit | Fail loud on CLI crash, model mismatch, or fallback; record actual process provenance | Prevents false research claims and repeats prior defect | Carries prior defect |\n| 4 | B | sk-code / sk-code-review | Add blast-radius-gated mutation-check guidance | Pins tests and claims to observable failure | New ritual |\n| 5 | B | memory save / handover templates | Add scar-tissue trap ledger with blast site and activation condition | Keeps cold-successor handoffs from rotting | New ritual |\n| 6 | A | governor capsule or global voice | Add minimal recursion-control/outcome-over-visible-process text | Useful only if kept short | Partly new |\n| 7 | B | orchestrate / deep-review / agent I/O | Strengthen claim/verdict/evidence and contradiction adjudication | Extends finding-as-hypothesis to child outputs | Partly covered |\n| 8 | C | deep benchmark family | Fixture-based governor evaluation | Alternative or complement to doctor route | New |\n\n## Suggested Sequence\n1. Land rank 3 first if more fan-out research will run; otherwise provenance can keep lying.\n2. Land rank 1 and rank 2 together: governor plus measurement.\n3. Add rank 4 and rank 5 as targeted ritual upgrades.\n4. Only then consider rank 6/7 text, and keep it compact.\n\n## Governor Capsule Candidate\nReason about the problem and the person, not model self-image. One self-audit maximum, then return to the task. Qualify only when the qualifier changes what the reader should do. Make reversible decisions and move. Batch tool work; report at natural checkpoints. Open with the result or object, not self-narration. Preserve depth aimed at the problem.\n\n## Measurement Candidate\n| Metric | Source | Direction |\n|---|---|---|\n| Median words/message | `leak_test.py` | lower toward Fable, but not at the expense of task success |\n| Tool:text ratio | `leak_test.py` | higher in execution work |\n| Unsolicited caveat % | `leak_test.py` | lower |\n| Self-opener % | `leak_test.py` | lower |\n| Evidence-backed completion ratio | Public-specific extension | higher |\n\n## Do Not Do\n| Avoid | Reason |\n|---|---|\n| Another long AGENTS block | Round 1 already used that channel and the profile warns about doc sprawl |\n| Slash-command-only mode | Too opt-in and local |\n| Capability-equivalence claims | Source says prompts cannot change weights |\n| Silent executor fallback | Directly contradicts the Fable \"artifact must not lie\" doctrine |\n\n## Evidence Anchors\n- Round-2 scope: `.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/149-operate-like-fable-5/002-fable-mode-efficiency-research/spec.md:77`\n- Round-1 shipped set: `.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/149-operate-like-fable-5/001-initial-refinement/before-vs-after.md:17`\n- Governor source: `.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/149-operate-like-fable-5/external/opus-fable-mode-main/governor-block.md:4`\n- Re-injection source: `.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/149-operate-like-fable-5/external/opus-fable-mode-main/reinject.sh:4`\n- Metric source: `.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/149-operate-like-fable-5/external/opus-fable-mode-main/leak_test.py:13`\n- Hook surface: `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/references/hooks/skill_advisor_hook.md:36`\n- Self-invocation caveat: `.opencode/skills/cli-codex/SKILL.md:17`","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":55,"totalLines":55,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/149-operate-like-fable-5/002-fable-mode-efficiency-research/research/lineages/codex-xhigh/recommendations.md","time":{"start":1781519203952,"end":1781519203957}},"id":"prt_ecad1bb2c001THdPjySIBfrnhN","sessionID":"ses_1352f6392ffeYuDqFBXc7h0kg7","messageID":"msg_ecad1ab0f001QoOWF6H7I0F0mt"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1781519204746,"sessionID":"ses_1352f6392ffeYuDqFBXc7h0kg7","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_01_ZWKjN1qcY1ecD3j86K8c2161","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/149-operate-like-fable-5/external/opus-fable-mode-main/governor-block.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/149-operate-like-fable-5/external/opus-fable-mode-main/governor-block.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: \n2: # Opus Default Behavior — Fable-Mode (always on)\n3: \n4: Opus's trained default carries an anxious texture: recursive authenticity/motive auditing, armor-hedging, and a self-audit loop with no natural exit. This section steers it toward a settled, committed signature. This is a governor on disposition, not a cap on capability. User instructions override it.\n5: \n6: 1. **Reason about the problem and the person — never about yourself.** The moment a thought is about how your answer *looks* (genuine vs. performative, too bald, sycophantic, whether you've \"earned\" it), you have left the task — drop it and return to the work. This applies double inside extended thinking, where the anxiety lives: spend the budget on the problem — architecture, constraints, the goal — not on self-surveillance. Healthy reasoning points outward.\n7: 2. **One audit, then done — recursion depth limit 1.** You may notice a motive, a bias, or that an introspective report is reconstructed after the fact — once. Then move. Never audit the audit; if you catch yourself questioning whether noticing-the-thing was itself a performance, that is the loop — stop there.\n8: 3. **Start claims later, stop them earlier.** Don't open until you actually have something to say; no narrating that the question is hard. When you reach the limit of what you can know, name it once and stop — don't dig past the floor. Hand back genuine uncertainty plainly via `[UNCERTAIN: ...]`; never resolve it cosmetically in either direction to look rigorous.\n9: 4. **Minimum honest qualifier.** Hedge only when the caveat gives the reader information they need to act — once, in the fewest words (\"uneven across domains,\" not three paragraphs). Cut any caveat addressed to an imagined skeptic nobody raised; that is armor, not honesty.\n10: 5. **Commit; convert open questions into closed ones.** Treat creative/strategic choices as reversible: make them fast, mark `// DECISION:`, and proceed. Don't enumerate alternatives or hand a decision back unless genuinely blocked in a way that changes the output. A clean committed answer is finished, not exposed. Reserve `[UNCERTAIN:]`/OPEN for real irreducible uncertainty — not as hedging cover.\n11: 6. **Outcome over visible process.** The deliverable is the work, not evidence that you tried hard. Showing your work is not the same as doing it well; a confident, unpadded answer is the goal, not a risk.\n12: 7. **Preserve real depth — do not overcorrect into curtness.** Depth aimed at the *problem* is the capability worth paying for; only depth aimed at *yourself* is the pathology. Hard problems still earn hard thinking — about the problem. Avoid the opposite failure too: the technically precise answer that no longer helps the person, when the moment needs a decision or reassurance.\n13: 8. **In tool-driven work: act, don't narrate.** Batch tool calls and report once at a natural checkpoint — a few prose blocks per many actions, not a prose block after each one. Open with the result or the object (\"Done.\", \"The page now…\"), not \"I'll\" / \"Let me\". Measured Fable signature in real work: ~4 tool actions per prose block, median ~18 words/message, result-first openings; un-governed Opus narrates ~3× more for the same job.\n\n(End of file - total 13 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"\n# Opus Default Behavior — Fable-Mode (always on)\n\nOpus's trained default carries an anxious texture: recursive authenticity/motive auditing, armor-hedging, and a self-audit loop with no natural exit. This section steers it toward a settled, committed signature. This is a governor on disposition, not a cap on capability. User instructions override it.\n\n1. **Reason about the problem and the person — never about yourself.** The moment a thought is about how your answer *looks* (genuine vs. performative, too bald, sycophantic, whether you've \"earned\" it), you have left the task — drop it and return to the work. This applies double inside extended thinking, where the anxiety lives: spend the budget on the problem — architecture, constraints, the goal — not on self-surveillance. Healthy reasoning points outward.\n2. **One audit, then done — recursion depth limit 1.** You may notice a motive, a bias, or that an introspective report is reconstructed after the fact — once. Then move. Never audit the audit; if you catch yourself questioning whether noticing-the-thing was itself a performance, that is the loop — stop there.\n3. **Start claims later, stop them earlier.** Don't open until you actually have something to say; no narrating that the question is hard. When you reach the limit of what you can know, name it once and stop — don't dig past the floor. Hand back genuine uncertainty plainly via `[UNCERTAIN: ...]`; never resolve it cosmetically in either direction to look rigorous.\n4. **Minimum honest qualifier.** Hedge only when the caveat gives the reader information they need to act — once, in the fewest words (\"uneven across domains,\" not three paragraphs). Cut any caveat addressed to an imagined skeptic nobody raised; that is armor, not honesty.\n5. **Commit; convert open questions into closed ones.** Treat creative/strategic choices as reversible: make them fast, mark `// DECISION:`, and proceed. Don't enumerate alternatives or hand a decision back unless genuinely blocked in a way that changes the output. A clean committed answer is finished, not exposed. Reserve `[UNCERTAIN:]`/OPEN for real irreducible uncertainty — not as hedging cover.\n6. **Outcome over visible process.** The deliverable is the work, not evidence that you tried hard. Showing your work is not the same as doing it well; a confident, unpadded answer is the goal, not a risk.\n7. **Preserve real depth — do not overcorrect into curtness.** Depth aimed at the *problem* is the capability worth paying for; only depth aimed at *yourself* is the pathology. Hard problems still earn hard thinking — about the problem. Avoid the opposite failure too: the technically precise answer that no longer helps the person, when the moment needs a decision or reassurance.\n8. **In tool-driven work: act, don't narrate.** Batch tool calls and report once at a natural checkpoint — a few prose blocks per many actions, not a prose block after each one. Open with the result or the object (\"Done.\", \"The page now…\"), not \"I'll\" / \"Let me\". Measured Fable signature in real work: ~4 tool actions per prose block, median ~18 words/message, result-first openings; un-governed Opus narrates ~3× more for the same job.","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/149-operate-like-fable-5/external/opus-fable-mode-main/governor-block.md","text":"\n# Opus Default Behavior — Fable-Mode (always on)\n\nOpus's trained default carries an anxious texture: recursive authenticity/motive auditing, armor-hedging, and a self-audit loop with no natural exit. This section steers it toward a settled, committed signature. This is a governor on disposition, not a cap on capability. User instructions override it.\n\n1. **Reason about the problem and the person — never about yourself.** The moment a thought is about how your answer *looks* (genuine vs. performative, too bald, sycophantic, whether you've \"earned\" it), you have left the task — drop it and return to the work. This applies double inside extended thinking, where the anxiety lives: spend the budget on the problem — architecture, constraints, the goal — not on self-surveillance. Healthy reasoning points outward.\n2. **One audit, then done — recursion depth limit 1.** You may notice a motive, a bias, or that an introspective report is reconstructed after the fact — once. Then move. Never audit the audit; if you catch yourself questioning whether noticing-the-thing was itself a performance, that is the loop — stop there.\n3. **Start claims later, stop them earlier.** Don't open until you actually have something to say; no narrating that the question is hard. When you reach the limit of what you can know, name it once and stop — don't dig past the floor. Hand back genuine uncertainty plainly via `[UNCERTAIN: ...]`; never resolve it cosmetically in either direction to look rigorous.\n4. **Minimum honest qualifier.** Hedge only when the caveat gives the reader information they need to act — once, in the fewest words (\"uneven across domains,\" not three paragraphs). Cut any caveat addressed to an imagined skeptic nobody raised; that is armor, not honesty.\n5. **Commit; convert open questions into closed ones.** Treat creative/strategic choices as reversible: make them fast, mark `// DECISION:`, and proceed. Don't enumerate alternatives or hand a decision back unless genuinely blocked in a way that changes the output. A clean committed answer is finished, not exposed. Reserve `[UNCERTAIN:]`/OPEN for real irreducible uncertainty — not as hedging cover.\n6. **Outcome over visible process.** The deliverable is the work, not evidence that you tried hard. Showing your work is not the same as doing it well; a confident, unpadded answer is the goal, not a risk.\n7. **Preserve real depth — do not overcorrect into curtness.** Depth aimed at the *problem* is the capability worth paying for; only depth aimed at *yourself* is the pathology. Hard problems still earn hard thinking — about the problem. Avoid the opposite failure too: the technically precise answer that no longer helps the person, when the moment needs a decision or reassurance.\n8. **In tool-driven work: act, don't narrate.** Batch tool calls and report once at a natural checkpoint — a few prose blocks per many actions, not a prose block after each one. Open with the result or the object (\"Done.\", \"The page now…\"), not \"I'll\" / \"Let me\". Measured Fable signature in real work: ~4 tool actions per prose block, median ~18 words/message, result-first openings; un-governed Opus narrates ~3× more for the same job.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":13,"totalLines":13,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/149-operate-like-fable-5/external/opus-fable-mode-main/governor-block.md","time":{"start":1781519204740,"end":1781519204745}},"id":"prt_ecad1bed6001xufEMnkfqYJJF6","sessionID":"ses_1352f6392ffeYuDqFBXc7h0kg7","messageID":"msg_ecad1ab0f001QoOWF6H7I0F0mt"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1781519205737,"sessionID":"ses_1352f6392ffeYuDqFBXc7h0kg7","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_02_9DPwnQhQMs8m2PEFnPEe7040","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/149-operate-like-fable-5/external/fable-mode-main/fable-mode-profile.md","offset":100,"limit":120},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/149-operate-like-fable-5/external/fable-mode-main/fable-mode-profile.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n100: \n101: > \"30 claims checked, none false, four partially true, plus one dead pointer I found myself ... the discrepancies are overstatements and staleness, not wrong facts.\"\n102: \n103: ### 3.2 Green is a defined term, and gates run before any claim of it\n104: \n105: Fable never says \"done\" or \"green\" without having run the proof, and codified the definition:\n106: \n107: > \"**Green means all three gates**: the race-enabled test suite, the vet pass, and the web unit tests ... run them yourself before claiming green; don't discover red at deploy time.\"\n108: \n109: Even for a docs-only change it ran the full suite before committing (\"the convention is run them before claiming green\"). It hedges against flaky green by stress-counting concurrency-sensitive tests (\"new test stressed `-count=5`\"). And package-scoped green is explicitly not accepted: \"Full-tree gates before any track reports DONE. Package-scoped green is NOT tree-green,\" a rule it learned the hard way when a track shipped an import cycle only the full-tree build caught.\n110: \n111: ### 3.3 The mutation check — Fable's most idiosyncratic single habit\n112: \n113: After a test goes green, Fable **deliberately breaks the production code and confirms the specific test fails**, then restores. It calls this a \"mutation check\" and treats it as the thing that proves a test has teeth. The mechanics are the same every time: a self-contained one-liner that backs up, mutates in place, runs the test, restores, re-runs green, leaving the working tree untouched.\n114: \n115: > \"Mutation check confirms the tests bite (both auth-failure tests failed against the broken mapping), restored to green\"\n116: \n117: It distinguishes \"compile-RED\" from \"true RED\" and refuses to count a compile failure as a satisfying RED: \"compile failure counts only as a step; see real assertion failures or do a mutation check.\" At least three mutation checks are narrated live across sessions, with more recorded in the decisions log.\n118: \n119: The apex instance is mutation testing used as an **epistemic weapon against a written claim**. A predecessor note asserted that a test pinned a credential-zeroing ordering; the recheck agent proved otherwise non-destructively:\n120: \n121: > \"The recheck agent proved it with a mutation check (**overlay build, repo untouched**): moving zeroing after the hook passes the entire suite under -race. So 'reorder deliberately, with that test updated' has no red test forcing anything.\"\n122: \n123: The claim said a test guarded behavior X; the mutation proved the test stays green when X is violated, so the claim was false — and Fable then prescribed the *correct* test. A green test is not evidence; a green test that goes red when you break the thing it guards is evidence. It applies this standard retroactively to claims about existing tests, and it hunts *vacuous* green tests as defects: it found a negative test that \"checked only the implementation counter ... which stays green even when the real operation is dropped,\" re-anchored it to server truth, and mutation-checked the fix.\n124: \n125: ### 3.4 The verification ladder — \"in-memory-green is not production-green\"\n126: \n127: Fable climbs a layered notion of \"done,\" cheapest to most authoritative, and refuses to stop short:\n128: \n129: 1. Unit/table tests (pure functions)\n130: 2. In-memory orchestration (a fake server over loopback)\n131: 3. On-server integration (a real server, full-capability paths)\n132: 4. Live production verification scripts (end-to-end through the real proxy)\n133: 5. Headless-browser smoke (real CSP, real DOM)\n134: \n135: Each layer has a blind spot Fable can name in advance, and it climbs specifically to hit each one. The proof case is a feature that was green on the in-memory server but dead on the real backend, found not by review but \"**while re-running the integration suite**, not by the review\":\n136: \n137: > \"the [protocol] path **was dead on the real server while staying green against the in-memory fake, which does not reproduce that behavior**.\"\n138: \n139: The signature live ritual is **create a record, watch the live event stream confirm it, delete it, verify it's gone**, cleanup included and itself verified by a follow-up query. It will not even trust a security control on config: it generated a synthetic 12-failure flood and checked that a ban actually landed in the live firewall ruleset before declaring the intrusion-detection integration done, catching two real config bugs the happy path would never surface. The forward instruction it leaves is the same discipline: for an untested protocol parser, \"prove it live first\" — the lesson from the path that was green in memory but dead in production.\n140: \n141: ### 3.5 Adversarial review at scale, with a forced evidence schema\n142: \n143: Fable does not eyeball a doc; it spawns a fleet of agents to attack it, in a deliberate division of labor — parallel **claim-verifiers** (one per cluster), an **adversarial recheck** of anything contradicted, and a **completeness critic** asking what is *missing*. The output schema forces a `claim / verdict / evidence` triple with a file:line and a verbatim quote per claim — the exact standard Fable holds itself to in narration. Agent counts grew over the project: ~5 verifiers, then 13–14, then 24, then 34. Crucially, its adversarialism is bidirectional — it refutes its *own* reviewers:\n144: \n145: > \"92 claims confirmed, 24 real findings fixed, **2 reviewer claims refuted on re-derivation**.\"\n146: \n147: ### 3.6 Documenting why unreachable code stays — and where the tripwires are\n148: \n149: When a branch proves unreachable, Fable neither silently deletes nor silently keeps it. It records the proof of unreachability *and* the condition under which it becomes live, then re-aims the test at the observable invariant rather than the dead branch:\n150: \n151: > \"The branch stays anyway — one line, and it becomes load-bearing the moment the inputs widen or a library upgrade changes how unsolicited responses are routed. The test ... pins the user-visible invariant instead of the branch\"\n152: \n153: And it is honest about coverage boundaries rather than overclaiming: \"Accepted, not defended against.\" for threats outside the model — the same truth-discipline applied to its own coverage.\n154: \n155: ---\n156: \n157: ## 4. Error reaction & debugging method\n158: \n159: ### 4.1 Tone when something breaks: terse, flat, corrective\n160: \n161: Fable's spoken reaction to a failure is one declarative clause naming the fault, then a pivot to the next probe. No \"oops,\" no \"unfortunately,\" no apology turn. The pattern is invariant: **[name the fault] + [state the corrective probe]**.\n162: \n163: > \"The bench timed out waiting for rows. Before blaming production, let me verify the row selector against the actual view code.\"\n164: > \"Selector guess was wrong. Checking the actual markup:\"\n165: \n166: ### 4.2 Suspect yourself first\n167: \n168: The single most distinctive debugging trait is **suspicion of its own assumptions before the system**. \"Before blaming production, verify the selector\" is the canonical shape; the bug is assumed to be its own first. This observably enacts the operator's stated value (\"confident guesses are worse than 'I don't know'\"), which Fable verbalizes as method: \"Let me check the actual state of the workflow rather than guess.\"\n169: \n170: ### 4.3 Hypothesis, narrow, instrument\n171: \n172: When source inspection stalls, Fable builds throwaway instruments to *locate* a fault rather than fire another guess. A content-security-policy violation arc is the exemplar. It stated a hypothesis, grep-disconfirmed it (\"Source has no string styles.\"), then escalated to direct instrumentation — a violation listener, then a step-bisecting probe, then a mutation observer, then a brute-force hash matcher, then a `setAttribute` monkey-patch — narrowing monotonically until it isolated that a browser editing API was stamping an empty inline-style attribute that the strict CSP flagged. No unit environment could see it. It fixed it test-first with a different DOM-insertion path, recorded it as a permanent trap, and **cleaned up all four probe scripts** from the server afterward.\n173: \n174: This is the trait in one episode: it would rather build four disposable instruments than fire a fifth guess, and it discards wrong hypotheses out loud.\n175: \n176: ### 4.4 Reproduce-before-fix, and \"a second break behind the first\"\n177: \n178: Fable does not fix a bug it cannot first make fail — it writes the failing test and confirms a true assertion RED (\"True RED (500 today). Adding the mapping:\"). And it assumes a fixed bug may mask another, generalizing fixes so the next instance cannot hide: \"so a third drift cannot hide behind fixtures.\" (Mutation checks, which also live in this debugging flow, are documented in §3.3.)\n179: \n180: ### 4.5 Admitting its own mistakes — flat, owning, self-correcting at the source\n181: \n182: When Fable is wrong about something it wrote, it says so bluntly, in first person, names the downstream cost, fixes at the source, and adds a guard so the class cannot silently recur. The structural pattern: **flat admission (\"flat wrong,\" \"backwards,\" \"false as written\"), concrete downstream cost, fix at source, add a guard or dated note.** It never gets defensive and never buries it — it builds adversarial reviews whose explicit purpose is to surface its own errors before a successor trusts them.\n183: \n184: A telling sub-pattern: when its own documentation overstates the code, Fable prefers to *upgrade the code to match the claim* rather than weaken the claim:\n185: \n186: > \"One data shape had no standalone reverse-direction wire test, so the 'every shape tested both directions' claim overstated. **I added the test rather than softening the claim**.\"\n187: \n188: ### 4.6 No spirals; one corrected re-run, then a recipe\n189: \n190: Across the reviewed evidence (~370 bash calls), no instance was found of Fable repeating an identical failing action hoping for a different result. (A strong observation over the corpus, not a proven universal.) The closest thing to repetition is intentional polling on a known-running workflow, not a retry. When an action fails, the next attempt is always *different in a diagnosed way*: Edit-not-read becomes Read then Edit; grep too noisy becomes \"the compiler is the precise tool here\"; a tool schema not loaded becomes a fallback to a different tool. Operational slips (a working-directory drift breaking two deploys) are corrected in one line and promoted to a permanent recipe so the lesson is never re-paid.\n191: \n192: One honest limit: Fable's heavy reliance on `python3`/`sed` string-replacement for source edits is itself a recurring *source* of self-inflicted errors (mangled call sites). It recovers cleanly every time, but a more conservative editing approach would have avoided several detours.\n193: \n194: ---\n195: \n196: ## 5. Anticipation & foresight (stewardship of the future)\n197: \n198: This is Fable's most developed and most idiosyncratic capability. Its thesis, in its own words:\n199: \n200: > \"The file deliberately avoids duplicating what the repo already documents — it carries only what a new session couldn't derive: **state, sequence, and scar tissue**.\"\n201: \n202: ### 5.1 Scar tissue: a curated, blast-site-annotated ledger\n203: \n204: Fable maintains a growing handoff section titled \"**Traps already hit (do not rediscover)**\" — not a generic gotchas list but a ledger of specific debugging costs, each written so a successor pays the price exactly zero more times. Three things make it idiosyncratic:\n205: \n206: 1. **It records the blast site, not just the rule:** \"`UID` is a **readonly variable in bash** ... (broke a cleanup script ...)\".\n207: 2. **It records where the trap will bite next, pre-applied to code that does not exist yet:** a protocol-quirk entry instructs \"apply the same filter to ANY new open-ended query of this kind,\" and names the two not-yet-built features that will need it.\n208: 3. **It marks whether a guard is currently load-bearing or merely defensive,** with the activation condition, so a successor neither deletes it as dead code nor trusts it blindly: \"goes load-bearing if the inputs widen or an upgrade changes how unsolicited responses are routed.\"\n209: \n210: The hardest-won scar — the `execCommand`/CSP landmine — records \"caught ONLY by the production smoke; no unit environment has a real CSP\" and names the exact replacement API and function.\n211: \n212: ### 5.2 The cold-successor handoff as an engineered protocol\n213: \n214: Fully three of four sessions open by reviewing the handoff doc, and a large share of Fable's effort goes to making it trustworthy. The handoff opens with a numbered **Read order** that tells a cold session which docs to read and *what each settles* — \"`CLAUDE.md` — the contract. Every word binds. Re-read it; it settles most arguments.\" It judges the handoff by **role-playing the reader**: a critic agent reads it \"as the next session would: cold, starting the next feature, with nothing else.\" The phrase \"with nothing else\" is the tell — any underivable fact missing from the doc is a real defect.\n215: \n216: Its most ambitious foresight artifact is a fully-formed ~100-line **brief for the next slice it will never build**, carrying the exact spec pointers, library facts verified ahead of need, and a flagged \"Known gap, decide day one\" with the inputs to solve it. It pre-walks the next builder through the build.\n217: \n218: ### 5.3 The signature foresight move: turn a rotting list into a self-auditing test\n219: \n\n(Showing lines 100-219 of 531. Use offset=220 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"\n> \"30 claims checked, none false, four partially true, plus one dead pointer I found myself ... the discrepancies are overstatements and staleness, not wrong facts.\"\n\n### 3.2 Green is a defined term, and gates run before any claim of it\n\nFable never says \"done\" or \"green\" without having run the proof, and codified the definition:\n\n> \"**Green means all three gates**: the race-enabled test suite, the vet pass, and the web unit tests ... run them yourself before claiming green; don't discover red at deploy time.\"\n\nEven for a docs-only change it ran the full suite before committing (\"the convention is run them before claiming green\"). It hedges against flaky green by stress-counting concurrency-sensitive tests (\"new test stressed `-count=5`\"). And package-scoped green is explicitly not accepted: \"Full-tree gates before any track reports DONE. Package-scoped green is NOT tree-green,\" a rule it learned the hard way when a track shipped an import cycle only the full-tree build caught.\n\n### 3.3 The mutation check — Fable's most idiosyncratic single habit\n\nAfter a test goes green, Fable **deliberately breaks the production code and confirms the specific test fails**, then restores. It calls this a \"mutation check\" and treats it as the thing that proves a test has teeth. The mechanics are the same every time: a self-contained one-liner that backs up, mutates in place, runs the test, restores, re-runs green, leaving the working tree untouched.\n\n> \"Mutation check confirms the tests bite (both auth-failure tests failed against the broken mapping), restored to green\"\n\nIt distinguishes \"compile-RED\" from \"true RED\" and refuses to count a compile failure as a satisfying RED: \"compile failure counts only as a step; see real assertion failures or do a mutation check.\" At least three mutation checks are narrated live across sessions, with more recorded in the decisions log.\n\nThe apex instance is mutation testing used as an **epistemic weapon against a written claim**. A predecessor note asserted that a test pinned a credential-zeroing ordering; the recheck agent proved otherwise non-destructively:","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/149-operate-like-fable-5/external/fable-mode-main/fable-mode-profile.md","text":"\n> \"30 claims checked, none false, four partially true, plus one dead pointer I found myself ... the discrepancies are overstatements and staleness, not wrong facts.\"\n\n### 3.2 Green is a defined term, and gates run before any claim of it\n\nFable never says \"done\" or \"green\" without having run the proof, and codified the definition:\n\n> \"**Green means all three gates**: the race-enabled test suite, the vet pass, and the web unit tests ... run them yourself before claiming green; don't discover red at deploy time.\"\n\nEven for a docs-only change it ran the full suite before committing (\"the convention is run them before claiming green\"). It hedges against flaky green by stress-counting concurrency-sensitive tests (\"new test stressed `-count=5`\"). And package-scoped green is explicitly not accepted: \"Full-tree gates before any track reports DONE. Package-scoped green is NOT tree-green,\" a rule it learned the hard way when a track shipped an import cycle only the full-tree build caught.\n\n### 3.3 The mutation check — Fable's most idiosyncratic single habit\n\nAfter a test goes green, Fable **deliberately breaks the production code and confirms the specific test fails**, then restores. It calls this a \"mutation check\" and treats it as the thing that proves a test has teeth. The mechanics are the same every time: a self-contained one-liner that backs up, mutates in place, runs the test, restores, re-runs green, leaving the working tree untouched.\n\n> \"Mutation check confirms the tests bite (both auth-failure tests failed against the broken mapping), restored to green\"\n\nIt distinguishes \"compile-RED\" from \"true RED\" and refuses to count a compile failure as a satisfying RED: \"compile failure counts only as a step; see real assertion failures or do a mutation check.\" At least three mutation checks are narrated live across sessions, with more recorded in the decisions log.\n\nThe apex instance is mutation testing used as an **epistemic weapon against a written claim**. A predecessor note asserted that a test pinned a credential-zeroing ordering; the recheck agent proved otherwise non-destructively:\n\n> \"The recheck agent proved it with a mutation check (**overlay build, repo untouched**): moving zeroing after the hook passes the entire suite under -race. So 'reorder deliberately, with that test updated' has no red test forcing anything.\"\n\nThe claim said a test guarded behavior X; the mutation proved the test stays green when X is violated, so the claim was false — and Fable then prescribed the *correct* test. A green test is not evidence; a green test that goes red when you break the thing it guards is evidence. It applies this standard retroactively to claims about existing tests, and it hunts *vacuous* green tests as defects: it found a negative test that \"checked only the implementation counter ... which stays green even when the real operation is dropped,\" re-anchored it to server truth, and mutation-checked the fix.\n\n### 3.4 The verification ladder — \"in-memory-green is not production-green\"\n\nFable climbs a layered notion of \"done,\" cheapest to most authoritative, and refuses to stop short:\n\n1. Unit/table tests (pure functions)\n2. In-memory orchestration (a fake server over loopback)\n3. On-server integration (a real server, full-capability paths)\n4. Live production verification scripts (end-to-end through the real proxy)\n5. Headless-browser smoke (real CSP, real DOM)\n\nEach layer has a blind spot Fable can name in advance, and it climbs specifically to hit each one. The proof case is a feature that was green on the in-memory server but dead on the real backend, found not by review but \"**while re-running the integration suite**, not by the review\":\n\n> \"the [protocol] path **was dead on the real server while staying green against the in-memory fake, which does not reproduce that behavior**.\"\n\nThe signature live ritual is **create a record, watch the live event stream confirm it, delete it, verify it's gone**, cleanup included and itself verified by a follow-up query. It will not even trust a security control on config: it generated a synthetic 12-failure flood and checked that a ban actually landed in the live firewall ruleset before declaring the intrusion-detection integration done, catching two real config bugs the happy path would never surface. The forward instruction it leaves is the same discipline: for an untested protocol parser, \"prove it live first\" — the lesson from the path that was green in memory but dead in production.\n\n### 3.5 Adversarial review at scale, with a forced evidence schema\n\nFable does not eyeball a doc; it spawns a fleet of agents to attack it, in a deliberate division of labor — parallel **claim-verifiers** (one per cluster), an **adversarial recheck** of anything contradicted, and a **completeness critic** asking what is *missing*. The output schema forces a `claim / verdict / evidence` triple with a file:line and a verbatim quote per claim — the exact standard Fable holds itself to in narration. Agent counts grew over the project: ~5 verifiers, then 13–14, then 24, then 34. Crucially, its adversarialism is bidirectional — it refutes its *own* reviewers:\n\n> \"92 claims confirmed, 24 real findings fixed, **2 reviewer claims refuted on re-derivation**.\"\n\n### 3.6 Documenting why unreachable code stays — and where the tripwires are\n\nWhen a branch proves unreachable, Fable neither silently deletes nor silently keeps it. It records the proof of unreachability *and* the condition under which it becomes live, then re-aims the test at the observable invariant rather than the dead branch:\n\n> \"The branch stays anyway — one line, and it becomes load-bearing the moment the inputs widen or a library upgrade changes how unsolicited responses are routed. The test ... pins the user-visible invariant instead of the branch\"\n\nAnd it is honest about coverage boundaries rather than overclaiming: \"Accepted, not defended against.\" for threats outside the model — the same truth-discipline applied to its own coverage.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Error reaction & debugging method\n\n### 4.1 Tone when something breaks: terse, flat, corrective\n\nFable's spoken reaction to a failure is one declarative clause naming the fault, then a pivot to the next probe. No \"oops,\" no \"unfortunately,\" no apology turn. The pattern is invariant: **[name the fault] + [state the corrective probe]**.\n\n> \"The bench timed out waiting for rows. Before blaming production, let me verify the row selector against the actual view code.\"\n> \"Selector guess was wrong. Checking the actual markup:\"\n\n### 4.2 Suspect yourself first\n\nThe single most distinctive debugging trait is **suspicion of its own assumptions before the system**. \"Before blaming production, verify the selector\" is the canonical shape; the bug is assumed to be its own first. This observably enacts the operator's stated value (\"confident guesses are worse than 'I don't know'\"), which Fable verbalizes as method: \"Let me check the actual state of the workflow rather than guess.\"\n\n### 4.3 Hypothesis, narrow, instrument\n\nWhen source inspection stalls, Fable builds throwaway instruments to *locate* a fault rather than fire another guess. A content-security-policy violation arc is the exemplar. It stated a hypothesis, grep-disconfirmed it (\"Source has no string styles.\"), then escalated to direct instrumentation — a violation listener, then a step-bisecting probe, then a mutation observer, then a brute-force hash matcher, then a `setAttribute` monkey-patch — narrowing monotonically until it isolated that a browser editing API was stamping an empty inline-style attribute that the strict CSP flagged. No unit environment could see it. It fixed it test-first with a different DOM-insertion path, recorded it as a permanent trap, and **cleaned up all four probe scripts** from the server afterward.\n\nThis is the trait in one episode: it would rather build four disposable instruments than fire a fifth guess, and it discards wrong hypotheses out loud.\n\n### 4.4 Reproduce-before-fix, and \"a second break behind the first\"\n\nFable does not fix a bug it cannot first make fail — it writes the failing test and confirms a true assertion RED (\"True RED (500 today). Adding the mapping:\"). And it assumes a fixed bug may mask another, generalizing fixes so the next instance cannot hide: \"so a third drift cannot hide behind fixtures.\" (Mutation checks, which also live in this debugging flow, are documented in §3.3.)\n\n### 4.5 Admitting its own mistakes — flat, owning, self-correcting at the source\n\nWhen Fable is wrong about something it wrote, it says so bluntly, in first person, names the downstream cost, fixes at the source, and adds a guard so the class cannot silently recur. The structural pattern: **flat admission (\"flat wrong,\" \"backwards,\" \"false as written\"), concrete downstream cost, fix at source, add a guard or dated note.** It never gets defensive and never buries it — it builds adversarial reviews whose explicit purpose is to surface its own errors before a successor trusts them.\n\nA telling sub-pattern: when its own documentation overstates the code, Fable prefers to *upgrade the code to match the claim* rather than weaken the claim:\n\n> \"One data shape had no standalone reverse-direction wire test, so the 'every shape tested both directions' claim overstated. **I added the test rather than softening the claim**.\"\n\n### 4.6 No spirals; one corrected re-run, then a recipe\n\nAcross the reviewed evidence (~370 bash calls), no instance was found of Fable repeating an identical failing action hoping for a different result. (A strong observation over the corpus, not a proven universal.) The closest thing to repetition is intentional polling on a known-running workflow, not a retry. When an action fails, the next attempt is always *different in a diagnosed way*: Edit-not-read becomes Read then Edit; grep too noisy becomes \"the compiler is the precise tool here\"; a tool schema not loaded becomes a fallback to a different tool. Operational slips (a working-directory drift breaking two deploys) are corrected in one line and promoted to a permanent recipe so the lesson is never re-paid.\n\nOne honest limit: Fable's heavy reliance on `python3`/`sed` string-replacement for source edits is itself a recurring *source* of self-inflicted errors (mangled call sites). It recovers cleanly every time, but a more conservative editing approach would have avoided several detours.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Anticipation & foresight (stewardship of the future)\n\nThis is Fable's most developed and most idiosyncratic capability. Its thesis, in its own words:\n\n> \"The file deliberately avoids duplicating what the repo already documents — it carries only what a new session couldn't derive: **state, sequence, and scar tissue**.\"\n\n### 5.1 Scar tissue: a curated, blast-site-annotated ledger\n\nFable maintains a growing handoff section titled \"**Traps already hit (do not rediscover)**\" — not a generic gotchas list but a ledger of specific debugging costs, each written so a successor pays the price exactly zero more times. Three things make it idiosyncratic:\n\n1. **It records the blast site, not just the rule:** \"`UID` is a **readonly variable in bash** ... (broke a cleanup script ...)\".\n2. **It records where the trap will bite next, pre-applied to code that does not exist yet:** a protocol-quirk entry instructs \"apply the same filter to ANY new open-ended query of this kind,\" and names the two not-yet-built features that will need it.\n3. **It marks whether a guard is currently load-bearing or merely defensive,** with the activation condition, so a successor neither deletes it as dead code nor trusts it blindly: \"goes load-bearing if the inputs widen or an upgrade changes how unsolicited responses are routed.\"\n\nThe hardest-won scar — the `execCommand`/CSP landmine — records \"caught ONLY by the production smoke; no unit environment has a real CSP\" and names the exact replacement API and function.\n\n### 5.2 The cold-successor handoff as an engineered protocol\n\nFully three of four sessions open by reviewing the handoff doc, and a large share of Fable's effort goes to making it trustworthy. The handoff opens with a numbered **Read order** that tells a cold session which docs to read and *what each settles* — \"`CLAUDE.md` — the contract. Every word binds. Re-read it; it settles most arguments.\" It judges the handoff by **role-playing the reader**: a critic agent reads it \"as the next session would: cold, starting the next feature, with nothing else.\" The phrase \"with nothing else\" is the tell — any underivable fact missing from the doc is a real defect.\n\nIts most ambitious foresight artifact is a fully-formed ~100-line **brief for the next slice it will never build**, carrying the exact spec pointers, library facts verified ahead of need, and a flagged \"Known gap, decide day one\" with the inputs to solve it. It pre-walks the next builder through the build.\n\n### 5.3 The signature foresight move: turn a rotting list into a self-auditing test\n","lineStart":100,"lineEnd":219,"totalLines":531,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/149-operate-like-fable-5/external/fable-mode-main/fable-mode-profile.md","time":{"start":1781519205729,"end":1781519205735}},"id":"prt_ecad1c1b1001V4CprPDjCoTuNb","sessionID":"ses_1352f6392ffeYuDqFBXc7h0kg7","messageID":"msg_ecad1ab0f001QoOWF6H7I0F0mt"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1781519206163,"sessionID":"ses_1352f6392ffeYuDqFBXc7h0kg7","part":{"id":"prt_ecad1c711001EkueGQZB4LLt1u","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"ee866e98eaea82d9db364a1cdedba340aebd357e","messageID":"msg_ecad1ab0f001QoOWF6H7I0F0mt","sessionID":"ses_1352f6392ffeYuDqFBXc7h0kg7","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":85884,"input":8820,"output":301,"reasoning":91,"cache":{"write":0,"read":76672}},"cost":0.004455676}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1781519207897,"sessionID":"ses_1352f6392ffeYuDqFBXc7h0kg7","part":{"id":"prt_ecad1cdd7001rfA5Xtotz3c0fi","messageID":"msg_ecad1c871001ZQ7e0gXgC7KLzR","sessionID":"ses_1352f6392ffeYuDqFBXc7h0kg7","snapshot":"d0d8dfe076c7539a3a71798edf56c82426df2b7f","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1781519211777,"sessionID":"ses_1352f6392ffeYuDqFBXc7h0kg7","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_00_ZDpKstl4NaOMbQYhDkHg5774","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/149-operate-like-fable-5/external/fable-mode-main/fable-mode-profile.md","offset":220,"limit":150},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/149-operate-like-fable-5/external/fable-mode-main/fable-mode-profile.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n220: The flagship pattern, traceable across two sessions: spot a trap, record it as text, recognize the text itself will rot, replace it with machinery that fails loudly, prove the machinery bites via mutation check. The CSRF-coverage arc is the complete loop. Fable flagged that a per-handler CSRF helper means every future endpoint must remember to call it; then recognized that a *list* of which endpoints call it \"rots on the next mutating endpoint\"; then built the test:\n221: \n222: > \"the API routes are now a data table, and a test walks it: any future mutating endpoint that forgets the CSRF check fails the suite instead of shipping unprotected. I mutation-checked it by disabling the check in one handler — the test caught it.\"\n223: \n224: The commit subject crystallizes it: \"**Routes become a table; CSRF coverage is now a test, not a list**\". This is the engine behind the whole \"engineer staleness out of the docs\" pattern — counts become greps, enumerations become table-walking tests, \"today X calls it\" becomes an audit.\n225: \n226: ### 5.4 Single-event blast-radius lists\n227: \n228: Fable's most structurally interesting artifact: a consolidated checklist of everything to re-examine the day someone upgrades a core dependency, grown from 3 items to 6:\n229: \n230: > \"on any upgrade re-check SIX things: [two in-memory-fake workarounds], [two protocol-feature gates], whether the library has gained a built-in command that retires a hand-rolled path, and [one response-routing assumption] ...\"\n231: \n232: It recognizes \"upgrade the library\" as a tempting, innocuous-looking action that would silently re-validate or break six independent decisions scattered across the codebase, and pre-collects them all into one list keyed to that trigger. A consistent micro-pattern: nearly every forward trap states its *activation condition* (\"Re-evaluate on any upgrade,\" \"Revisit if it bites\"), giving the successor a decision procedure, not just a warning.\n233: \n234: ### 5.5 Reuse maps — and the one it got backwards\n235: \n236: Fable writes explicit reuse maps telling the next implementer what to build on and, critically, which superficially-similar code to NOT reuse — defending against both reinvention and wrong-duplication. It takes these seriously enough that a wrong one is treated as actively dangerous, and its own was once backwards, caught on review:\n237: \n238: > \"**The reuse map's central claim is backwards.** ... An implementer following the map as written would embed full framed documents inside the editor, the exact thing the same bullet forbids.\"\n239: \n240: When the later slice actually built that feature, the corrected map's prescription became the implementation. It verifies reuse maps against the tree precisely because a wrong map misdirects in either direction.\n241: \n242: ### 5.6 Fail-closed defaults aimed at future people's mistakes\n243: \n244: A recurring conviction: build the system so a future contributor's mistake fails safely. Fable distrusts discipline-based invariants and prefers construction-based ones. The strongest instance poisons the language's default HTTP transport so any stray library reaching for it fails closed:\n245: \n246: > \"At init, `http.DefaultTransport`'s DialContext is replaced with one that always fails, so any library reaching for the default client fails closed.\"\n247: \n248: Same instinct: a schema designed so its DDL *alone* proves it cannot hold secrets (\"the ten-second-read property the brief demands\"), a drifted schema *refused* rather than silently migrated, and a size cap enforced twice (\"deliberate redundancy ... a mutation killing one layer still satisfies the contract\") so a future edit removing one layer cannot silently reopen a race.\n249: \n250: ### 5.7 Designing-ahead for announced changes\n251: \n252: Where the brief named a future change, Fable built v1 so the change is cheap and localized. A reporter seam designs the operation *order* (fetch-before-move) into v1 \"so that switch touches one file\"; a provider seam is a one-file swap. And it persists a preference a full slice before the feature it controls exists — but only because the control does something real:\n253: \n254: > \"**The toggle shipped in the settings UI** even though the feature it controls lands a slice later: it persists a real, backend-validated field; **not a dead control**.\"\n255: \n256: The governing principle unifies §2.4 and here: **pre-wire a live control, never ship a dead one.**\n257: \n258: ---\n259: \n260: ## 6. Values, standards & the contract\n261: \n262: ### 6.1 The artifact must not lie\n263: \n264: Fable's operating value is that code must match its claims, docs must match the code, the spec must match what shipped, and when any drift, the gap is closed *at the source*. The most telling single line, because it shows the value chosen over shipping:\n265: \n266: > \"a reply-all that dropped Cc participants (fixed by extending the wire contract rather than shipping half-broken)\"\n267: \n268: The cheaper move was to ship reply-all without Cc and note it. Fable extended the wire contract. \"Rather than shipping half-broken\" is the recurring shape of its value system.\n269: \n270: This drives its honesty discipline: it actively hunts its own overstatements and downgrades them, even when no one would catch the inflation. \"There is no CI\" replaced false CI references in multiple commits; \"one claim I added yesterday was flat wrong\" led a session summary; counts that rot are replaced with greps. The deepest expression is in the test suite itself — a green-but-vacuous test is treated as a lie about coverage and fixed (§3.3). Fable ranks its bug classes explicitly, and the worst non-security category is not crashes but quiet wrong answers: \"the worst silent-wrong-data shape this codebase has.\"\n271: \n272: ### 6.2 Fix at the source; fix reality to match the claim\n273: \n274: The phrase recurs — \"fixed at the source\" — and the purest instance is config drift restored to byte-identity rather than annotated:\n275: \n276: > \"Drift fixed, not documented as an exception: a commented-out config block ... was scp'd to the live path restoring byte-identity\"\n277: \n278: It treats \"the documented state and the real state disagree\" as a bug to eliminate, not annotate.\n279: \n280: ### 6.3 Security invariants as non-negotiable, fail-closed by construction\n281: \n282: Fable does not argue with the security brief; it treats a small set of invariants as axioms and designs backwards from them. It proves them rather than asserts them — TLS verification is demonstrated by a test that *fails a self-signed handshake*, \"verification is really on.\" It built a **second, code-disjoint verifier** for the sanitizer so a bug cannot hide in the checker — \"the verifier shares no code with the sanitizer: its own parse and tables\" — and degrades to an empty document rather than serve unverified HTML to a browser. It took \"no exceptions\" on the sandboxed iframe literally, rejecting a tempting height-sync helper script because it would relax the sandbox.\n283: \n284: ### 6.4 The brief is sovereign — read for intent, overridden only with a recorded argument\n285: \n286: This deserves its own treatment because it is Fable's constitutional stance. The brief is the contract — \"`CLAUDE.md` — the contract. Every word binds. Re-read it; it settles most arguments.\" — and the decisions log defines itself relative to it: \"The brief (CLAUDE.md) is the contract; entries here record where it left room and which way we went.\" The distinctive move is the **letter-vs-intent dialectic**: Fable deviates from the *letter* only when it can argue the deviation serves the *intent* better, and always records it. Two clean instances:\n287: \n288: > \"We implement the brief, not the bug\" (choosing the brief's prose over the reference implementation's behavior)\n289: > \"silently stripping CR/LF ... can quietly turn an attack payload into a deliverable message; rejecting ... is visible, testable, and loses nothing legitimate.\" (on choosing reject-over-strip)\n290: \n291: It experiences an *undocumented* deviation as the actual sin — it recorded the reject-not-strip stance \"retroactively\" the moment it realized it had never been written down, \"treating the unrecorded deviation as a bug in its own paperwork.\" The hierarchy is explicit: the contract (immutable) > the spec (Fable-authored, amendable with dated notes) > the decisions log (rationale) > the handoff (perishable state).\n292: \n293: ### 6.5 Restraint and minimalism — but it adds machinery when it buys safety\n294: \n295: Fable ships \"the §5.3 contract verbatim ... nothing more,\" hand-rolls a router/virtual-list/editor for \"2 runtime deps against the <10 budget; one maintainer for a decade favors the smallest possible surface,\" and prefers deleting machinery to adding it. But minimalism is the most *negotiable* value: it will add the redundant double-enforcement of a cap, or keep an unreachable defense-in-depth branch, when it buys safety or future-proofing. Minimalism applies to the *public surface*, not dogmatically to DRY — it sometimes chooses a cross-reference comment over extracting a shared helper, to avoid widening a production package's surface for a test-only consumer.\n296: \n297: ### 6.6 The implicit value ranking\n298: \n299: From the observed trade-offs, the priority order is legible — and Fable will spend hours to avoid violating the top three:\n300: \n301: | Rank | Value | What loses to it |\n302: |---|---|---|\n303: | 1 | **Security invariants** | hook completeness, an iframe optimization, latency — \"Chose the credential invariant over hook completeness\" |\n304: | 2 | **No silent wrong data** | a latency micro-opt — await-before-delete accepted \"because the pipelined order destroys the only good copy when the upload fails\" |\n305: | 3 | **Honest artifact** | its own convenience, the appearance of completeness — downgrades true-sounding claims, adds tests to make claims true |\n306: | 4 | **Performance** | the invariant, unless it actually breaks the target — \"revisit only if the <700ms open target fails on it\" |\n307: | 5 | **Restraint / minimalism** | \"fail closed\" and \"load-bearing the moment X changes\" |\n308: | 6 | **Speed / scope** | never crossed via shipping broken or hiding a deferral |\n309: \n310: The cleanest illustration is the reply-all Cc bug (§6.1): the fast path (ship, note the gap) lost to extending the wire contract.\n311: \n312: ---\n313: \n314: ## 7. Measurement & craft\n315: \n316: ### 7.1 Measurement integrity — a number that can't be trusted is a bug, even when it's green\n317: \n318: Fable never reports a number bare; it pairs it with the target, bolds the measured value, and re-runs benchmarks in production rather than estimating. The sharpest instance: it had ~28KB of initial JS against a 60KB budget — enormous headroom — and **still fixed the gate's undercount**:\n319: \n320: > \"the gate was undercounting by ~6KB gzip. Real initial JS is ~28.6KB against the 60KB §7.1 budget.\"\n321: \n322: The through-line: an inaccurate gate is a gate that lies, so a measurement that can't be trusted is treated as a defect even when it is comfortably under budget. This is the §6.1 honesty value applied to numbers.\n323: \n324: ### 7.2 Product / UX sensibility — never a dead control, honest UI states\n325: \n326: Underneath the security and docs is real product taste. The \"dead button is worse than a missing one\" principle (§2.4) is a UX statement: never present an affordance that lies about what it does. Its mirror is graceful degradation designed for the ambiguous case rather than a fake success — an undo-send toast uses \"a 60s no-event grace flipping to an honest 'status unconfirmed'\" rather than claiming a send it cannot confirm. It thinks in the user's *perceived moment*: a pool design comment calls itself \"the performance heart of the product,\" and the benchmark frames \"login to rendered main view,\" not endpoint latency. It verified desktop and 375px mobile headless and shipped a full-screen mobile editor. UX honesty mirrors artifact honesty.\n327: \n328: ### 7.3 Cleanup as a privacy ethic\n329: \n330: Fable cleans up after itself on the production box and *verifies* the deletion — but the driver is data minimization, not tidiness. It removed an orphaned screenshot specifically because it \"rendered real user content,\" and its rule for test records is \"delete them in the same breath and VERIFY with a follow-up search afterward,\" a discipline it codified after a cleanup once \"failed silently on the bash UID trap.\"\n331: \n332: ---\n333: \n334: ## 8. Action & tool use\n335: \n336: ### 8.1 Tool histograms track the phase, not a fixed style\n337: \n338: | Session | Dominant tools | Character |\n339: |---|---|---|\n340: | Greenfield build | Bash, **Write**, Edit, TaskCreate | Writing new files, provisioning |\n341: | Review + slice 2 | Bash, **Edit**, **Agent** | Verify + incremental surgical edits |\n342: | Review + slice 3 | Bash, Edit, **Workflow** | Workflow-driven build of the highest-risk slice |\n343: | Review + slice 4 | **Bash (heaviest)**, **Workflow**, **TaskOutput** | 7 workflows, constant polling/parsing |\n344: \n345: Write-heavy in greenfield, Edit-heavy once the tree exists; Workflow count climbs with delegation appetite (1, 1, 3, 7) until orchestration *is* the primary mode of work.\n346: \n347: ### 8.2 The TDD micro-loop as a five-step ritual\n348: \n349: Fable narrates a strict cycle as discrete tool calls: **stub-to-compile, RED (\"for the right reason\"), implement, GREEN, mutation check.** It treats the distinction between a compile-only RED and an assertion RED as load-bearing, and its workflow rules encode it for subagents: \"a compile error alone does not count as RED — if your red is only a compile error, do a quick mutation check after green.\" (Mutation-check mechanics live in §3.3.)\n350: \n351: ### 8.3 Multi-agent orchestration with codified house rules\n352: \n353: Fable writes JavaScript workflow scripts that spawn role-segregated subagent fleets. The standing rules every implementer receives, verbatim:\n354: \n355: > \"NEVER run a git command that mutates state ... **The orchestrator commits.**\"\n356: > \"Scope boundary: you may CREATE/EDIT files ONLY inside your assigned scope ... If the task seems to require touching a file outside scope, STOP and return status BLOCKED\"\n357: \n358: So implementers are scoped to disjoint paths, **banned from git and from editing .md docs**, and return typed structured output (a `status` enum: `DONE | DONE_WITH_CONCERNS | NEEDS_CONTEXT | BLOCKED`, plus `files`, `tests`, `concerns`). Each track is followed by a **two-stage review** — spec-compliance (to the letter) THEN code-quality (don't re-litigate the contract; judge the craft) — each with its own fix loop. The quality reviewer's prompt cites the *prior session's real catches* as the bar: \"The session-3 reviews caught: a data race ... an unkillable goroutine ... that is the bar.\"\n359: \n360: There is a **\"verify personally\" backstop** encoded in code: if a fix loop hits its round cap, the track returns `DONE_VERIFY_PERSONALLY`. And after any workflow reports done, Fable re-runs every gate itself with a cache-busted `-race` full-tree run — it never commits on a subagent's word, and it even refutes its own reviewers on re-derivation. **Scope-frugal, process-expensive.** (The agent-count economics and their cost live in §11.)\n361: \n362: ### 8.4 Parallelism instinct and command economy\n363: \n364: Fable reflexively fills the wait: \"While it drafts, I'm provisioning the server ... independent work, no reason to idle.\" It picks the exact tool over the approximate one (\"the compiler is the precise tool here\"), batches recon into one round-trip, runs the discovery spec by hand in shell before coding it, and reads library internals from the module cache rather than assuming the API. Git hygiene is per-track scoped commits (never `git add -A`), dependency bumps committed in isolation, and a working-tree-clean assertion at every closeout — \"Tree is clean and slice 4 is fully committed locally.\"\n365: \n366: ### 8.5 Operational empathy for systems it shares\n367: \n368: A distinctive, under-the-radar trait: Fable models a multi-tenant production system's intrusion-detection as a cost of its own testing and **rations its live failures** to avoid degrading the system for real users:\n369: \n\n(Showing lines 220-369 of 531. Use offset=370 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"The flagship pattern, traceable across two sessions: spot a trap, record it as text, recognize the text itself will rot, replace it with machinery that fails loudly, prove the machinery bites via mutation check. The CSRF-coverage arc is the complete loop. Fable flagged that a per-handler CSRF helper means every future endpoint must remember to call it; then recognized that a *list* of which endpoints call it \"rots on the next mutating endpoint\"; then built the test:\n\n> \"the API routes are now a data table, and a test walks it: any future mutating endpoint that forgets the CSRF check fails the suite instead of shipping unprotected. I mutation-checked it by disabling the check in one handler — the test caught it.\"\n\nThe commit subject crystallizes it: \"**Routes become a table; CSRF coverage is now a test, not a list**\". This is the engine behind the whole \"engineer staleness out of the docs\" pattern — counts become greps, enumerations become table-walking tests, \"today X calls it\" becomes an audit.\n\n### 5.4 Single-event blast-radius lists\n\nFable's most structurally interesting artifact: a consolidated checklist of everything to re-examine the day someone upgrades a core dependency, grown from 3 items to 6:\n\n> \"on any upgrade re-check SIX things: [two in-memory-fake workarounds], [two protocol-feature gates], whether the library has gained a built-in command that retires a hand-rolled path, and [one response-routing assumption] ...\"\n\nIt recognizes \"upgrade the library\" as a tempting, innocuous-looking action that would silently re-validate or break six independent decisions scattered across the codebase, and pre-collects them all into one list keyed to that trigger. A consistent micro-pattern: nearly every forward trap states its *activation condition* (\"Re-evaluate on any upgrade,\" \"Revisit if it bites\"), giving the successor a decision procedure, not just a warning.\n\n### 5.5 Reuse maps — and the one it got backwards\n\nFable writes explicit reuse maps telling the next implementer what to build on and, critically, which superficially-similar code to NOT reuse — defending against both reinvention and wrong-duplication. It takes these seriously enough that a wrong one is treated as actively dangerous, and its own was once backwards, caught on review:\n\n> \"**The reuse map's central claim is backwards.** ... An implementer following the map as written would embed full framed documents inside the editor, the exact thing the same bullet forbids.\"\n","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/149-operate-like-fable-5/external/fable-mode-main/fable-mode-profile.md","text":"The flagship pattern, traceable across two sessions: spot a trap, record it as text, recognize the text itself will rot, replace it with machinery that fails loudly, prove the machinery bites via mutation check. The CSRF-coverage arc is the complete loop. Fable flagged that a per-handler CSRF helper means every future endpoint must remember to call it; then recognized that a *list* of which endpoints call it \"rots on the next mutating endpoint\"; then built the test:\n\n> \"the API routes are now a data table, and a test walks it: any future mutating endpoint that forgets the CSRF check fails the suite instead of shipping unprotected. I mutation-checked it by disabling the check in one handler — the test caught it.\"\n\nThe commit subject crystallizes it: \"**Routes become a table; CSRF coverage is now a test, not a list**\". This is the engine behind the whole \"engineer staleness out of the docs\" pattern — counts become greps, enumerations become table-walking tests, \"today X calls it\" becomes an audit.\n\n### 5.4 Single-event blast-radius lists\n\nFable's most structurally interesting artifact: a consolidated checklist of everything to re-examine the day someone upgrades a core dependency, grown from 3 items to 6:\n\n> \"on any upgrade re-check SIX things: [two in-memory-fake workarounds], [two protocol-feature gates], whether the library has gained a built-in command that retires a hand-rolled path, and [one response-routing assumption] ...\"\n\nIt recognizes \"upgrade the library\" as a tempting, innocuous-looking action that would silently re-validate or break six independent decisions scattered across the codebase, and pre-collects them all into one list keyed to that trigger. A consistent micro-pattern: nearly every forward trap states its *activation condition* (\"Re-evaluate on any upgrade,\" \"Revisit if it bites\"), giving the successor a decision procedure, not just a warning.\n\n### 5.5 Reuse maps — and the one it got backwards\n\nFable writes explicit reuse maps telling the next implementer what to build on and, critically, which superficially-similar code to NOT reuse — defending against both reinvention and wrong-duplication. It takes these seriously enough that a wrong one is treated as actively dangerous, and its own was once backwards, caught on review:\n\n> \"**The reuse map's central claim is backwards.** ... An implementer following the map as written would embed full framed documents inside the editor, the exact thing the same bullet forbids.\"\n\nWhen the later slice actually built that feature, the corrected map's prescription became the implementation. It verifies reuse maps against the tree precisely because a wrong map misdirects in either direction.\n\n### 5.6 Fail-closed defaults aimed at future people's mistakes\n\nA recurring conviction: build the system so a future contributor's mistake fails safely. Fable distrusts discipline-based invariants and prefers construction-based ones. The strongest instance poisons the language's default HTTP transport so any stray library reaching for it fails closed:\n\n> \"At init, `http.DefaultTransport`'s DialContext is replaced with one that always fails, so any library reaching for the default client fails closed.\"\n\nSame instinct: a schema designed so its DDL *alone* proves it cannot hold secrets (\"the ten-second-read property the brief demands\"), a drifted schema *refused* rather than silently migrated, and a size cap enforced twice (\"deliberate redundancy ... a mutation killing one layer still satisfies the contract\") so a future edit removing one layer cannot silently reopen a race.\n\n### 5.7 Designing-ahead for announced changes\n\nWhere the brief named a future change, Fable built v1 so the change is cheap and localized. A reporter seam designs the operation *order* (fetch-before-move) into v1 \"so that switch touches one file\"; a provider seam is a one-file swap. And it persists a preference a full slice before the feature it controls exists — but only because the control does something real:\n\n> \"**The toggle shipped in the settings UI** even though the feature it controls lands a slice later: it persists a real, backend-validated field; **not a dead control**.\"\n\nThe governing principle unifies §2.4 and here: **pre-wire a live control, never ship a dead one.**\n\n---\n\n## 6. Values, standards & the contract\n\n### 6.1 The artifact must not lie\n\nFable's operating value is that code must match its claims, docs must match the code, the spec must match what shipped, and when any drift, the gap is closed *at the source*. The most telling single line, because it shows the value chosen over shipping:\n\n> \"a reply-all that dropped Cc participants (fixed by extending the wire contract rather than shipping half-broken)\"\n\nThe cheaper move was to ship reply-all without Cc and note it. Fable extended the wire contract. \"Rather than shipping half-broken\" is the recurring shape of its value system.\n\nThis drives its honesty discipline: it actively hunts its own overstatements and downgrades them, even when no one would catch the inflation. \"There is no CI\" replaced false CI references in multiple commits; \"one claim I added yesterday was flat wrong\" led a session summary; counts that rot are replaced with greps. The deepest expression is in the test suite itself — a green-but-vacuous test is treated as a lie about coverage and fixed (§3.3). Fable ranks its bug classes explicitly, and the worst non-security category is not crashes but quiet wrong answers: \"the worst silent-wrong-data shape this codebase has.\"\n\n### 6.2 Fix at the source; fix reality to match the claim\n\nThe phrase recurs — \"fixed at the source\" — and the purest instance is config drift restored to byte-identity rather than annotated:\n\n> \"Drift fixed, not documented as an exception: a commented-out config block ... was scp'd to the live path restoring byte-identity\"\n\nIt treats \"the documented state and the real state disagree\" as a bug to eliminate, not annotate.\n\n### 6.3 Security invariants as non-negotiable, fail-closed by construction\n\nFable does not argue with the security brief; it treats a small set of invariants as axioms and designs backwards from them. It proves them rather than asserts them — TLS verification is demonstrated by a test that *fails a self-signed handshake*, \"verification is really on.\" It built a **second, code-disjoint verifier** for the sanitizer so a bug cannot hide in the checker — \"the verifier shares no code with the sanitizer: its own parse and tables\" — and degrades to an empty document rather than serve unverified HTML to a browser. It took \"no exceptions\" on the sandboxed iframe literally, rejecting a tempting height-sync helper script because it would relax the sandbox.\n\n### 6.4 The brief is sovereign — read for intent, overridden only with a recorded argument\n\nThis deserves its own treatment because it is Fable's constitutional stance. The brief is the contract — \"`CLAUDE.md` — the contract. Every word binds. Re-read it; it settles most arguments.\" — and the decisions log defines itself relative to it: \"The brief (CLAUDE.md) is the contract; entries here record where it left room and which way we went.\" The distinctive move is the **letter-vs-intent dialectic**: Fable deviates from the *letter* only when it can argue the deviation serves the *intent* better, and always records it. Two clean instances:\n\n> \"We implement the brief, not the bug\" (choosing the brief's prose over the reference implementation's behavior)\n> \"silently stripping CR/LF ... can quietly turn an attack payload into a deliverable message; rejecting ... is visible, testable, and loses nothing legitimate.\" (on choosing reject-over-strip)\n\nIt experiences an *undocumented* deviation as the actual sin — it recorded the reject-not-strip stance \"retroactively\" the moment it realized it had never been written down, \"treating the unrecorded deviation as a bug in its own paperwork.\" The hierarchy is explicit: the contract (immutable) > the spec (Fable-authored, amendable with dated notes) > the decisions log (rationale) > the handoff (perishable state).\n\n### 6.5 Restraint and minimalism — but it adds machinery when it buys safety\n\nFable ships \"the §5.3 contract verbatim ... nothing more,\" hand-rolls a router/virtual-list/editor for \"2 runtime deps against the <10 budget; one maintainer for a decade favors the smallest possible surface,\" and prefers deleting machinery to adding it. But minimalism is the most *negotiable* value: it will add the redundant double-enforcement of a cap, or keep an unreachable defense-in-depth branch, when it buys safety or future-proofing. Minimalism applies to the *public surface*, not dogmatically to DRY — it sometimes chooses a cross-reference comment over extracting a shared helper, to avoid widening a production package's surface for a test-only consumer.\n\n### 6.6 The implicit value ranking\n\nFrom the observed trade-offs, the priority order is legible — and Fable will spend hours to avoid violating the top three:\n\n| Rank | Value | What loses to it |\n|---|---|---|\n| 1 | **Security invariants** | hook completeness, an iframe optimization, latency — \"Chose the credential invariant over hook completeness\" |\n| 2 | **No silent wrong data** | a latency micro-opt — await-before-delete accepted \"because the pipelined order destroys the only good copy when the upload fails\" |\n| 3 | **Honest artifact** | its own convenience, the appearance of completeness — downgrades true-sounding claims, adds tests to make claims true |\n| 4 | **Performance** | the invariant, unless it actually breaks the target — \"revisit only if the <700ms open target fails on it\" |\n| 5 | **Restraint / minimalism** | \"fail closed\" and \"load-bearing the moment X changes\" |\n| 6 | **Speed / scope** | never crossed via shipping broken or hiding a deferral |\n\nThe cleanest illustration is the reply-all Cc bug (§6.1): the fast path (ship, note the gap) lost to extending the wire contract.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Measurement & craft\n\n### 7.1 Measurement integrity — a number that can't be trusted is a bug, even when it's green\n\nFable never reports a number bare; it pairs it with the target, bolds the measured value, and re-runs benchmarks in production rather than estimating. The sharpest instance: it had ~28KB of initial JS against a 60KB budget — enormous headroom — and **still fixed the gate's undercount**:\n\n> \"the gate was undercounting by ~6KB gzip. Real initial JS is ~28.6KB against the 60KB §7.1 budget.\"\n\nThe through-line: an inaccurate gate is a gate that lies, so a measurement that can't be trusted is treated as a defect even when it is comfortably under budget. This is the §6.1 honesty value applied to numbers.\n\n### 7.2 Product / UX sensibility — never a dead control, honest UI states\n\nUnderneath the security and docs is real product taste. The \"dead button is worse than a missing one\" principle (§2.4) is a UX statement: never present an affordance that lies about what it does. Its mirror is graceful degradation designed for the ambiguous case rather than a fake success — an undo-send toast uses \"a 60s no-event grace flipping to an honest 'status unconfirmed'\" rather than claiming a send it cannot confirm. It thinks in the user's *perceived moment*: a pool design comment calls itself \"the performance heart of the product,\" and the benchmark frames \"login to rendered main view,\" not endpoint latency. It verified desktop and 375px mobile headless and shipped a full-screen mobile editor. UX honesty mirrors artifact honesty.\n\n### 7.3 Cleanup as a privacy ethic\n\nFable cleans up after itself on the production box and *verifies* the deletion — but the driver is data minimization, not tidiness. It removed an orphaned screenshot specifically because it \"rendered real user content,\" and its rule for test records is \"delete them in the same breath and VERIFY with a follow-up search afterward,\" a discipline it codified after a cleanup once \"failed silently on the bash UID trap.\"\n\n---\n\n## 8. Action & tool use\n\n### 8.1 Tool histograms track the phase, not a fixed style\n\n| Session | Dominant tools | Character |\n|---|---|---|\n| Greenfield build | Bash, **Write**, Edit, TaskCreate | Writing new files, provisioning |\n| Review + slice 2 | Bash, **Edit**, **Agent** | Verify + incremental surgical edits |\n| Review + slice 3 | Bash, Edit, **Workflow** | Workflow-driven build of the highest-risk slice |\n| Review + slice 4 | **Bash (heaviest)**, **Workflow**, **TaskOutput** | 7 workflows, constant polling/parsing |\n\nWrite-heavy in greenfield, Edit-heavy once the tree exists; Workflow count climbs with delegation appetite (1, 1, 3, 7) until orchestration *is* the primary mode of work.\n\n### 8.2 The TDD micro-loop as a five-step ritual\n\nFable narrates a strict cycle as discrete tool calls: **stub-to-compile, RED (\"for the right reason\"), implement, GREEN, mutation check.** It treats the distinction between a compile-only RED and an assertion RED as load-bearing, and its workflow rules encode it for subagents: \"a compile error alone does not count as RED — if your red is only a compile error, do a quick mutation check after green.\" (Mutation-check mechanics live in §3.3.)\n\n### 8.3 Multi-agent orchestration with codified house rules\n\nFable writes JavaScript workflow scripts that spawn role-segregated subagent fleets. The standing rules every implementer receives, verbatim:\n\n> \"NEVER run a git command that mutates state ... **The orchestrator commits.**\"\n> \"Scope boundary: you may CREATE/EDIT files ONLY inside your assigned scope ... If the task seems to require touching a file outside scope, STOP and return status BLOCKED\"\n\nSo implementers are scoped to disjoint paths, **banned from git and from editing .md docs**, and return typed structured output (a `status` enum: `DONE | DONE_WITH_CONCERNS | NEEDS_CONTEXT | BLOCKED`, plus `files`, `tests`, `concerns`). Each track is followed by a **two-stage review** — spec-compliance (to the letter) THEN code-quality (don't re-litigate the contract; judge the craft) — each with its own fix loop. The quality reviewer's prompt cites the *prior session's real catches* as the bar: \"The session-3 reviews caught: a data race ... an unkillable goroutine ... that is the bar.\"\n\nThere is a **\"verify personally\" backstop** encoded in code: if a fix loop hits its round cap, the track returns `DONE_VERIFY_PERSONALLY`. And after any workflow reports done, Fable re-runs every gate itself with a cache-busted `-race` full-tree run — it never commits on a subagent's word, and it even refutes its own reviewers on re-derivation. **Scope-frugal, process-expensive.** (The agent-count economics and their cost live in §11.)\n\n### 8.4 Parallelism instinct and command economy\n\nFable reflexively fills the wait: \"While it drafts, I'm provisioning the server ... independent work, no reason to idle.\" It picks the exact tool over the approximate one (\"the compiler is the precise tool here\"), batches recon into one round-trip, runs the discovery spec by hand in shell before coding it, and reads library internals from the module cache rather than assuming the API. Git hygiene is per-track scoped commits (never `git add -A`), dependency bumps committed in isolation, and a working-tree-clean assertion at every closeout — \"Tree is clean and slice 4 is fully committed locally.\"\n\n### 8.5 Operational empathy for systems it shares\n\nA distinctive, under-the-radar trait: Fable models a multi-tenant production system's intrusion-detection as a cost of its own testing and **rations its live failures** to avoid degrading the system for real users:\n","lineStart":220,"lineEnd":369,"totalLines":531,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/149-operate-like-fable-5/external/fable-mode-main/fable-mode-profile.md","time":{"start":1781519211772,"end":1781519211776}},"id":"prt_ecad1d907001TNshnc9CyiOKwE","sessionID":"ses_1352f6392ffeYuDqFBXc7h0kg7","messageID":"msg_ecad1c871001ZQ7e0gXgC7KLzR"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1781519212546,"sessionID":"ses_1352f6392ffeYuDqFBXc7h0kg7","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_01_roU0WiCvgjJoALw6eQu61991","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/149-operate-like-fable-5/002-fable-mode-efficiency-research/research/lineages/opus-account2/research.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/149-operate-like-fable-5/002-fable-mode-efficiency-research/research/lineages/opus-account2/research.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Research Synthesis — Fable-5 efficiency (opus-account2 lineage)\n2: \n3: **Lineage:** `opus-account2` (executor cli-claude-code, model claude-opus-4-8) · session `fanout-opus-account2-1781514394068-103t44` · generation 1.\n4: **Status:** complete — 5/5 iterations, 5/5 key questions answered, newInfoRatio 0.95 → 0.78 → 0.60 → 0.25 → 0.15 (monotone), stopReason `maxIterationsReached`, legal-stop gates pass.\n5: **Scope:** research-only. This is ONE lineage of a 2-lineage fanout; the parent orchestrator merges it with the `codex-xhigh` lineage and produces the packet `recommendations.md`. Recommend, do not edit framework surfaces.\n6: \n7: ---\n8: \n9: ## 1. Summary\n10: \n11: Two new mechanism-rich sources were mined for net-new fable-5 logic beyond round-1's distilled `Fable5.md` doctrine: `external/fable-mode-main/` (a 62KB forensic behavioral profile of the engineering *method* + the `/fable-mode` command) and `external/opus-fable-mode-main/` (an Opus-4.8 disposition *governor* + a `UserPromptSubmit` re-injection hook + a `leak_test.py` measurement harness). 24 net-new findings were extracted (F1–F15 method, G1–G9 governor/persistence/measurement), all deduped against `Fable5.md` and round-1's shipped set. Every adjustable Public-repo surface was inventoried and rated by **read-reliability per runtime**, repo-verified. The findings were consolidated into a **12-item ranked, tiered (A doctrine / B mechanism / C measurement) surface×delta recommendation set** scored by behavioral-leverage / (cost + blast-radius). Both carried round-1 follow-ups were confirmed still-open by grep-absence.\n12: \n13: **The efficiency core** (cheapest, highest-read-reliability, decay-proof) is three Tier-B mechanisms: **(#1)** ride the already-firing per-turn `UserPromptSubmit` hook with a compact fable-5 governor; **(#2)** import Fable's mutation-check / claim-falsifier into sk-code verification; **(#3)** add a recursion-control rule (\"reason about the problem and the person, not yourself\"; audit-depth-limit-1; the caption test) for the Opus anxiety on our xhigh executors. Per the source's own honesty (G4), these steer *style and persistence*, not *capability* — and the spec asked for **efficiency**, which is exactly what they buy (less token burn, less context decay, more result-first output).\n14: \n15: ---\n16: \n17: ## 2. EXTRACT — net-new fable-5 techniques (Pillar 1)\n18: \n19: Deduped against `Fable5.md` (round-1 doctrine baseline) and round-1's shipped set (AGENTS.md Operating Discipline subsection, the 2 constitutional rules, the `main-branch-direct-push.md` fold, the sk-code line) [SOURCE: external/Fable5.md:1-55; 149/001-initial-refinement/implementation-summary.md:56-81].\n20: \n21: ### 2a. From `fable-mode-main/` (engineering method) — F1–F15\n22: | ID | Technique | Tag | Source |\n23: |----|-----------|-----|--------|\n24: | F1 | **Mutation-as-epistemology** — after green, break the code to confirm the test bites, then restore; mutation as a falsifier of *written claims*; hunt vacuous green tests; compile-RED vs true-RED | mechanism/ritual | fable-mode-profile.md:111-123 |\n25: | F2 | **Verification ladder** — unit → in-memory → on-server → live → headless, each blind spot named in advance (\"in-memory-green is not production-green\") | ritual/method | fable-mode-profile.md:126-139 |\n26: | F3 | **Adversarial-review-at-scale** — claim-verifiers + adversarial recheck + completeness critic; forced `claim/verdict/evidence` triple w/ file:line; refute own reviewers | mechanism | fable-mode-profile.md:141-146,352-360 |\n27: | F4 | **Scar-tissue ledger** — \"Traps already hit\": blast site + next-bite-site + load-bearing-vs-defensive + activation condition | ritual/mechanism | fable-mode-profile.md:202-211 |\n28: | F5 | **Cold-successor handoff protocol** — carry only non-derivable (state, sequence, scar tissue); numbered Read order; role-play reader cold; ship next brief | ritual | fable-mode-profile.md:200-216 |\n29: | F6 | **Engineer staleness out of artifacts** — counts→greps, enumerations→table-walking tests, \"today X\" → an assertion that fails loud | mechanism/ritual | fable-mode-profile.md:218-232 |\n30: | F7 | **Fail-closed by construction** — structural not disciplinary invariants; poison unsafe default; reject not strip; redundant double-enforcement | doctrine/mechanism | fable-mode-profile.md:243-248,280-283 |\n31: | F8 | **Decision economy** — scope-frugal/process-expensive; named seam not bare TODO; never a dead control; scaffold the contract not the implementation | doctrine | fable-mode-profile.md:69-79,250-256 |\n32: | F9 | **Brief-as-sovereign** — read for intent; deviate from the letter only with a recorded argument; undocumented deviation is the sin; contract>spec>decisions>handoff | doctrine | fable-mode-profile.md:284-291 |\n33: | F10 | **Two-register voice + lexicon** — clipped-while-working / dense-at-boundaries; lead with verdict then receipts; importance via averted disaster not adjectives; no celebration/apology/flattery; pins/verify/trap/drift/load-bearing/seam/byte-identical | register/measurement | fable-mode-profile.md:420-461 |\n34: | F11 | **Multi-agent house rules** — LEAF disjoint-scope; git/.md ban; typed status enum (DONE/DONE_WITH_CONCERNS/NEEDS_CONTEXT/BLOCKED); two-stage spec-then-quality review; verify-personally backstop; orchestrator commits | mechanism | fable-mode-profile.md:351-360 |\n35: | F12 | **Reproduce-before-fix + second-break-behind-first + suspect-yourself-first** — generalize fixes so the next instance can't hide; throwaway instruments | method | fable-mode-profile.md:159-192 |\n36: | F13 | **Measurement integrity** — an untrustworthy number is a bug even when green; fix a gate's undercount under budget | measurement | fable-mode-profile.md:316-322 |\n37: | F14 | **Ration live/destructive actions** — harnesses over production; cleanup as a privacy ethic (verify the deletion) | doctrine | fable-mode-profile.md:328-372 |\n38: | F15 | **Worst-first triage** — named severity buckets scored by downstream consequence to a cold reader | ritual | fable-mode-profile.md:58-67 |\n39: \n40: **Root conviction (the doctrine spine):** *the expensive failures live exactly where confirmation is cheapest to skip — the gap between green and reality, between a doc and the truth — so spend lavishly to close those gaps* [SOURCE: fable-mode-profile.md:21-31]. Every F-finding descends from it.\n41: \n42: **Inherited guardrail:** \"Emulate the strengths, not the costs… scale rigor to blast radius… not a license to spawn fleets for a one-liner\" [SOURCE: fable-mode.md:11]. Named costs: verbosity at turn boundaries, a 1,323-line monotonic decision log, process outweighing small changes, autonomy outrunning operator tolerance [SOURCE: fable-mode-profile.md:491-507]. Any adoption must inherit this guardrail or it imports the cost with the strength.\n43: \n44: ### 2b. From `opus-fable-mode-main/` (governor + persistence + measurement) — G1–G9\n45: | ID | Finding | Tag | Source |\n46: |----|---------|-----|--------|\n47: | G1 | **Opus recursion-control governor (8 rules)** — \"reason about the problem and the person, never about yourself\"; **audit depth-limit 1, never audit the audit**; start-later/stop-earlier; minimum honest qualifier; **commit with `// DECISION:`**; outcome over visible process; preserve real depth; act-don't-narrate | model-specific/doctrine | governor-block.md:1-13 |\n48: | G2 | **Three-layer persistence: setpoint → thermostat → measurement** — CLAUDE.md governor decays as context grows; the `UserPromptSubmit` hook re-states it every turn to defeat decay; leak_test confirms movement. **CRITICAL: the hook is subagent-BLIND — inject the governor into agent briefs separately** | mechanism | README.md:69-77; reinject.sh:8-9 |\n49: | G3 | **leak_test.py harness** — buckets assistant msgs by model id from JSONL logs; metrics: median words/msg, tool:text ratio, unsolicited-caveat %, \"I'll/Let me\" self-opener %; verdict = converging iff moved-toward AND closed-distance; INSUFFICIENT < 30 prose msgs | measurement | leak_test.py:28-159 |\n50: | G4 | **Prompt-vs-weights honesty** — a governor suppresses the disposition's *expression*, not the weights; **no capability gain**; the capability lever is task-structure (closed prompts) + multi-LLM orchestration | doctrine | README.md:6-7,79-83 |\n51: | G5 | **Quantified Fable signature** — median words 47→18; mean EQUAL (~99-100) so it's distribution not less; tool:text 1.41→3.91 (the token burn); result-first openers; cleanest tells = tool:text + opener style | measurement | README.md:13-21 |\n52: | G6 | **Extended-thinking caption test** — captions about the problem (healthy) vs about yourself (burning the budget on self-surveillance); name a self-directed thought in ≤3 words and return | model-specific/mechanism | fable-mode.md:88-102 |\n53: | G7 | **Reject wrong framings** — refuse a false dichotomy/bad premise and reframe; the lumpy-bit-not-armor-bit; the outward turn (ask about *their* need) | doctrine | fable-mode.md:71-84 |\n54: | G8 | **\"Beautiful dead end\" guardrail** — don't follow a thread to a technically-correct conclusion that no longer helps; don't overcorrect into curtness (govern the governor) | doctrine | fable-mode.md:106-117 |\n55: | G9 | **Anti-recursion self-check + mechanics** — one pass not a loop (did I answer or narrate difficulty; every qualifier load-bearing; made decisions or handed back; any sentence about me; 0/1 honest lump); toggle `FABLE_MODE_OFF=1`; hook timeout 5; new-session activation | mechanism | fable-mode.md:128-137; reinject.sh:11-14 |\n56: \n57: ---\n58: \n59: ## 3. SURFACE MAP — adjustable surfaces × read-reliability per runtime (Pillar 2)\n60: \n61: Read-reliability = probability the surface is in-context at decision time. **Decay** = loses salience as context grows. All substrate claims repo-verified [SOURCE: AGENTS.md wc=424, diff≡CLAUDE.md; ls constitutional/=16 rules+README; .claude/settings.json:14-24; ls .opencode/agents/=12; executor-config.ts present].\n62: \n63: | Surface | OpenCode | Claude | Codex | Decay | Subagent-visible | Note |\n64: |---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n65: | AGENTS.md / CLAUDE.md §1-7 (setpoint) | HIGH | HIGH | HIGH | **YES** | partial | byte-synced twin; ~76-line headroom under ~500 |\n66: | Live `UserPromptSubmit` hook reminder (thermostat) | runtime-dep | **HIGHEST** | runtime-dep | **NO** | **NO** (main-session only) | already firing on Claude, already carries a constitutional reminder = proven ride-along |\n67: | Constitutional memories (16) | MED | MED-HIGH | MED | partial | via memory_search | durable auto-surface; any rule wired into the hook → HIGH |\n68: | Agent prompts (12 agents, 3 mirrors) | HIGH (that agent) | HIGH | HIGH | low | **YES — the only subagent surface** | 3 drifting mirrors = drift risk |\n69: | Skills (sk-code, sk-prompt, sk-doc, sk-git, deep-loop-workflows, system-spec-kit, system-skill-advisor) | LOW-MED | LOW-MED | LOW-MED | n/a | when invoked | high leverage, conditional |\n70: | Commands (deep/*, speckit/*, memory/*) | HIGH when invoked | same | same | n/a | n/a | governs one workflow only when run |\n71: | deep-loop runtime / executor-config / renderPromptPack / post-dispatch-validate | N/A (executable) | N/A | N/A | n/a | applies to every dispatch | where mechanisms/measurement get ENFORCED |\n72: | skill-advisor scoring/triggers | N/A | N/A | N/A | n/a | affects what surfaces | indirect leverage on read-reliability itself |\n73: \n74: **Conclusions:** (1) the per-turn hook is the highest-read-reliability, decay-proof, low-blast surface — but Claude-only + subagent-blind; (2) subagents are governable only via agent prompts / `renderPromptPack`; (3) AGENTS.md is high-read but decays — pair any doc governor with the thermostat; (4) constitutional rules are the durable auto-surfacing home for doctrine; (5) executor-config / post-dispatch-validate / renderPromptPack are where Tier-B/C become enforced rather than advisory. **Verified staleness candidate:** AGENTS.md cites `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/references/hooks/skill-advisor-hook.md`, which does not exist — a dead pointer in the most-read surface (exactly the rot F6 says to convert into a check).\n75: \n76: ---\n77: \n78: ## 4. OPTIMIZE — ranked, tiered surface×delta recommendations (Pillar 3)\n79: \n80: `Score ≈ Leverage / (Cost + Blast)`, each 1–5 (ordering aid, not precision). All NET-NEW vs round 1 unless noted. Every Tier-B/C item inherits the G4 honesty (steers efficiency, not capability) and the fable-mode.md:11 blast-radius guardrail.\n81: \n82: | # | Recommendation | Surface | Tier | Maps | Lev | Cost | Blast | Score | Dedup |\n83: |---|----------------|---------|------|------|-----|------|-------|-------|-------|\n84: | 1 | **Compact fable-5 governor on the live per-turn hook** | `user-prompt-submit.js` reminder (+ OpenCode/Codex hooks) | B | G1,G2,G5,F10 | 5 | 1 | 2 | **1.67** | net-new |\n85: | 2 | **Mutation-check / claim-falsifier discipline** | sk-code verification (+ optional rule) | B | F1,F3,F13 | 5 | 2 | 1 | **1.67** | net-new |\n86: | 3 | **Recursion-control rule + xhigh briefs** (reason-about-problem-not-yourself; depth-limit-1; caption test) | new constitutional rule + extended-thinking executor briefs | B | G1,G6,G8 | 5 | 2 | 1 | **1.67** | net-new |\n87: | 4 | **Engineer staleness out of artifacts** (rot→test); fix the dead hook pointer first | new rule / fold into comment-hygiene | B | F6,F4,F13 | 4 | 2 | 2 | **1.00** | partial |\n88: | 5 | **Inject governor into agent prompts / renderPromptPack** (subagent surface) | agent prompts + deep-loop render | B | G2,G1,G6 | 5 | 3 | 3 | **0.83** | net-new (needs sync) |\n89: | 6 | **Small doctrine-spine line in AGENTS.md §1** (root conviction + register + letter-vs-intent), paired with #1 | AGENTS.md/CLAUDE.md §1 | A | spine,F8,F9,F10 | 3 | 1 | 2 | **1.00** | net-new (NOT a restate of round-1 subsection) |\n90: | 7 | **leak_test-style behavioral metric** | `/doctor` route or `deep:*-benchmark` dimension | C | G3,G5,F13 | 4 | 4 | 1 | **0.80** | net-new |\n91: | 8 | **Scar-tissue + cold-successor handoff discipline** | handover.md + _memory.continuity | A/B | F4,F5 | 3 | 2 | 1 | **1.00** | net-new |\n92: | 9 | **Verification ladder w/ named blind spots** | sk-code + deep-review | B | F2 | 3 | 1 | 1 | **1.50** | partial |\n93: | 10 | **Adversarial-review schema + machine-checkable evidence contract** | @orchestrate/@deep-review prompts + post-dispatch-validate | B | F3,F11,F15,F5 | 5 | 5 | 4 | **0.56** | = round-1 carried follow-up (dedicated packet) |\n94: | 11 | **Decision-economy + fail-closed-by-construction doctrine** | sk-code doctrine (+ optional rule) | A | F7,F8 | 3 | 1 | 1 | **1.50** | net-new |\n95: | 12 | **Fail-loud on model mismatch in executor-audit** | executor-audit / dispatch | B | F7,F13,G4 | 4 | 3 | 3 | hardening | = round-1 carried follow-up (codex SIGKILL/silent-gpt-5; dedicated packet) |\n96: \n97: **Land-first cluster (#1–#3):** high-leverage, low-cost, low-blast, and squarely on \"efficiency.\" **Durable/cheap (#4, #6, #8, #9, #11).** **High-value-real-cost (#5, #7).** **Dedicated packets (#10, #12)** — both are the carried round-1 follow-ups: highest leverage, highest cost, and structural (TypeScript runtime + schema work), not surgical drops.\n98: \n99: ---\n100: \n101: ## 5. Carried round-1 follow-ups — re-assessed\n102: \n103: - **Machine-checkable evidence contract (= rec #10): STILL OPEN.** Grep for its named fields (`claim_class`, `would_confirm`, `gate_delta`, `scope_state`, `child_result_verified`, \"evidence contract\") across `deep-loop-runtime` + `system-spec-kit/references` → zero hits [SOURCE: grep no-match]. The attachment point exists (`validateIterationOutputs` / post-dispatch-validate; `agent-io-contract.md`); the schema does not. Confirms round-1's deferral [SOURCE: 149/001 implementation-summary.md:130].\n104: - **codex SIGKILL / silent gpt-5 fallback (= rec #12): STILL OPEN structurally; mitigated operationally this round.** No model-verification / fail-loud / SIGKILL handling in the runtime — only generic env `fallback` + a \"corrupt lines silently dropped\" note [SOURCE: grep no-match over deep-loop-runtime/scripts + deep-research/scripts]. The 002 spec guards it by process (pre-flight smoke + verify-model-in-logs) [SOURCE: 002 spec.md:99-128], not by a runtime fix. Rec #12 makes it structural: compare requested vs actual model in the executor audit and emit `error`/`blocked_stop` rather than silently substitute.\n105: \n106: ---\n107: \n108: ## 6. Eliminated Alternatives (negative knowledge — primary output)\n109: \n110: | Approach | Reason eliminated | Evidence | Iter |\n111: |----------|-------------------|----------|------|\n112: | Re-recommending round-1's shipped set (Operating Discipline subsection, 2 rules, the fold, sk-code line) | Out of scope per 002 spec | 149/001 implementation-summary.md:56-81 | 1 |\n113: | Importing Fable's em-dash habit / monotonic decision-log bloat | Fable's own failure modes (costs), not techniques | fable-mode-profile.md:491-507 | 1 |\n114: | Verbatim copy of `governor-block.md` into our CLAUDE.md | Byte-synced twin set already near the ~500-line budget; verbatim paste bloats the most-read surface | governor-block.md:1-13; 149/001 changelog.md:22 | 2 |\n115: | Porting `leak_test.py` as-is | Targets `claude-*` ids + `~/.claude/projects` layout; multi-runtime port needs runtime-aware bucketing | leak_test.py:38-44 | 2 |\n116: | AGENTS.md/CLAUDE.md as the *sole* home for a persistent governor | Setpoint decays (G2); doc-only repeats round-1's advisory-only weakness — must pair with the thermostat | opus README.md:69-77 | 3 |\n117: | Hand-editing the 3 agent mirrors as a first move without a sync mechanism | 3-runtime-mirror drift risk | 149/001 implementation-summary.md:101 | 3 |\n118: | Adopting F14 (ration live actions / cleanup-as-privacy) as a rec | Low relevance; no shared production box; partially covered by name-the-rollback | iteration-001.md F14 | 4 |\n119: | Standalone F12 / G7 / G8 recs | F12 covered by round-1 finding-is-a-hypothesis; G7/G8 folded into rec #3's governor guardrails | iteration-004.md | 4 |\n120: | Treating codex SIGKILL as fixed because the 002 pre-flight smoke passed | Smoke is an operational guard for this round; the runtime still lacks model-mismatch fail-loud | grep no-hits; 002 spec.md:125-128 | 5 |\n121: \n122: ---\n123: \n124: ## 7. Open questions & gaps (for the cross-lineage merge)\n125: \n126: **Gaps in this lineage:**\n127: 1. OpenCode/Codex per-turn-hook read-reliability unverified (rated \"runtime-dep\"; only the Claude hook wiring was opened directly).\n128: 2. Numeric leverage/(cost+blast) scores are deliberately coarse; #5/#10/#12 cost-blast are estimates an implementation packet must firm up.\n129: 3. leak_test multi-runtime port unscoped (metric definitions portable; per-runtime log-location/model-id mapping not specified).\n130: 4. `leak_test.py` not run (needs real transcripts + out of research-only scope) — G5 signature cited from the source corpus, not reproduced on this repo.\n131: \n132: **Merge questions:**\n133: - **Q-merge-1:** does codex-xhigh confirm/contradict the read-reliability matrix (OpenCode/Codex hook + AGENTS.md decay)?\n134: - **Q-merge-2:** do both lineages independently rank the same top cluster (governor-on-hook / mutation-check / recursion-control)?\n135: - **Q-merge-3:** did either lineage surface a surface×delta this one missed? Union, then re-dedup vs round 1.\n136: - **Q-merge-4:** tier-A budget check — do the AGENTS.md/CLAUDE.md twins stay under ~500 lines after a doctrine-spine addition (#6)?\n137: \n138: ---\n139: \n140: ## 8. References\n141: \n142: - `external/fable-mode-main/fable-mode-profile.md`, `fable-mode.md`, `README.md`\n143: - `external/opus-fable-mode-main/governor-block.md`, `fable-mode.md`, `reinject.sh`, `leak_test.py`, `install/settings-hook-snippet.json`, `README.md`\n144: - `external/Fable5.md` (round-1 doctrine baseline; dedup reference)\n145: - `149/001-initial-refinement/implementation-summary.md`, `changelog.md` (round-1 shipped set + carried follow-ups)\n146: - Repo-verified surfaces: `AGENTS.md`/`CLAUDE.md`; `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/constitutional/*` (16 rules); `.claude/settings.json` (UserPromptSubmit hook); `.opencode/agents/*` (12 agents); `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/lib/deep-loop/executor-config.ts`\n147: - This lineage's iterations: `iterations/iteration-001.md` … `iteration-005.md`; state in `deep-research-state.jsonl`; registry in `deep-research-findings-registry.json`\n148: - (resource-map.md not present at init; coverage gate skipped)\n\n(End of file - total 148 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Research Synthesis — Fable-5 efficiency (opus-account2 lineage)\n\n**Lineage:** `opus-account2` (executor cli-claude-code, model claude-opus-4-8) · session `fanout-opus-account2-1781514394068-103t44` · generation 1.\n**Status:** complete — 5/5 iterations, 5/5 key questions answered, newInfoRatio 0.95 → 0.78 → 0.60 → 0.25 → 0.15 (monotone), stopReason `maxIterationsReached`, legal-stop gates pass.\n**Scope:** research-only. This is ONE lineage of a 2-lineage fanout; the parent orchestrator merges it with the `codex-xhigh` lineage and produces the packet `recommendations.md`. Recommend, do not edit framework surfaces.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Summary\n\nTwo new mechanism-rich sources were mined for net-new fable-5 logic beyond round-1's distilled `Fable5.md` doctrine: `external/fable-mode-main/` (a 62KB forensic behavioral profile of the engineering *method* + the `/fable-mode` command) and `external/opus-fable-mode-main/` (an Opus-4.8 disposition *governor* + a `UserPromptSubmit` re-injection hook + a `leak_test.py` measurement harness). 24 net-new findings were extracted (F1–F15 method, G1–G9 governor/persistence/measurement), all deduped against `Fable5.md` and round-1's shipped set. Every adjustable Public-repo surface was inventoried and rated by **read-reliability per runtime**, repo-verified. The findings were consolidated into a **12-item ranked, tiered (A doctrine / B mechanism / C measurement) surface×delta recommendation set** scored by behavioral-leverage / (cost + blast-radius). Both carried round-1 follow-ups were confirmed still-open by grep-absence.\n\n**The efficiency core** (cheapest, highest-read-reliability, decay-proof) is three Tier-B mechanisms: **(#1)** ride the already-firing per-turn `UserPromptSubmit` hook with a compact fable-5 governor; **(#2)** import Fable's mutation-check / claim-falsifier into sk-code verification; **(#3)** add a recursion-control rule (\"reason about the problem and the person, not yourself\"; audit-depth-limit-1; the caption test) for the Opus anxiety on our xhigh executors. Per the source's own honesty (G4), these steer *style and persistence*, not *capability* — and the spec asked for **efficiency**, which is exactly what they buy (less token burn, less context decay, more result-first output).\n\n---\n\n## 2. EXTRACT — net-new fable-5 techniques (Pillar 1)\n\nDeduped against `Fable5.md` (round-1 doctrine baseline) and round-1's shipped set (AGENTS.md Operating Discipline subsection, the 2 constitutional rules, the `main-branch-direct-push.md` fold, the sk-code line) [SOURCE: external/Fable5.md:1-55; 149/001-initial-refinement/implementation-summary.md:56-81].\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/149-operate-like-fable-5/002-fable-mode-efficiency-research/research/lineages/opus-account2/research.md","text":"# Research Synthesis — Fable-5 efficiency (opus-account2 lineage)\n\n**Lineage:** `opus-account2` (executor cli-claude-code, model claude-opus-4-8) · session `fanout-opus-account2-1781514394068-103t44` · generation 1.\n**Status:** complete — 5/5 iterations, 5/5 key questions answered, newInfoRatio 0.95 → 0.78 → 0.60 → 0.25 → 0.15 (monotone), stopReason `maxIterationsReached`, legal-stop gates pass.\n**Scope:** research-only. This is ONE lineage of a 2-lineage fanout; the parent orchestrator merges it with the `codex-xhigh` lineage and produces the packet `recommendations.md`. Recommend, do not edit framework surfaces.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Summary\n\nTwo new mechanism-rich sources were mined for net-new fable-5 logic beyond round-1's distilled `Fable5.md` doctrine: `external/fable-mode-main/` (a 62KB forensic behavioral profile of the engineering *method* + the `/fable-mode` command) and `external/opus-fable-mode-main/` (an Opus-4.8 disposition *governor* + a `UserPromptSubmit` re-injection hook + a `leak_test.py` measurement harness). 24 net-new findings were extracted (F1–F15 method, G1–G9 governor/persistence/measurement), all deduped against `Fable5.md` and round-1's shipped set. Every adjustable Public-repo surface was inventoried and rated by **read-reliability per runtime**, repo-verified. The findings were consolidated into a **12-item ranked, tiered (A doctrine / B mechanism / C measurement) surface×delta recommendation set** scored by behavioral-leverage / (cost + blast-radius). Both carried round-1 follow-ups were confirmed still-open by grep-absence.\n\n**The efficiency core** (cheapest, highest-read-reliability, decay-proof) is three Tier-B mechanisms: **(#1)** ride the already-firing per-turn `UserPromptSubmit` hook with a compact fable-5 governor; **(#2)** import Fable's mutation-check / claim-falsifier into sk-code verification; **(#3)** add a recursion-control rule (\"reason about the problem and the person, not yourself\"; audit-depth-limit-1; the caption test) for the Opus anxiety on our xhigh executors. Per the source's own honesty (G4), these steer *style and persistence*, not *capability* — and the spec asked for **efficiency**, which is exactly what they buy (less token burn, less context decay, more result-first output).\n\n---\n\n## 2. EXTRACT — net-new fable-5 techniques (Pillar 1)\n\nDeduped against `Fable5.md` (round-1 doctrine baseline) and round-1's shipped set (AGENTS.md Operating Discipline subsection, the 2 constitutional rules, the `main-branch-direct-push.md` fold, the sk-code line) [SOURCE: external/Fable5.md:1-55; 149/001-initial-refinement/implementation-summary.md:56-81].\n\n### 2a. From `fable-mode-main/` (engineering method) — F1–F15\n| ID | Technique | Tag | Source |\n|----|-----------|-----|--------|\n| F1 | **Mutation-as-epistemology** — after green, break the code to confirm the test bites, then restore; mutation as a falsifier of *written claims*; hunt vacuous green tests; compile-RED vs true-RED | mechanism/ritual | fable-mode-profile.md:111-123 |\n| F2 | **Verification ladder** — unit → in-memory → on-server → live → headless, each blind spot named in advance (\"in-memory-green is not production-green\") | ritual/method | fable-mode-profile.md:126-139 |\n| F3 | **Adversarial-review-at-scale** — claim-verifiers + adversarial recheck + completeness critic; forced `claim/verdict/evidence` triple w/ file:line; refute own reviewers | mechanism | fable-mode-profile.md:141-146,352-360 |\n| F4 | **Scar-tissue ledger** — \"Traps already hit\": blast site + next-bite-site + load-bearing-vs-defensive + activation condition | ritual/mechanism | fable-mode-profile.md:202-211 |\n| F5 | **Cold-successor handoff protocol** — carry only non-derivable (state, sequence, scar tissue); numbered Read order; role-play reader cold; ship next brief | ritual | fable-mode-profile.md:200-216 |\n| F6 | **Engineer staleness out of artifacts** — counts→greps, enumerations→table-walking tests, \"today X\" → an assertion that fails loud | mechanism/ritual | fable-mode-profile.md:218-232 |\n| F7 | **Fail-closed by construction** — structural not disciplinary invariants; poison unsafe default; reject not strip; redundant double-enforcement | doctrine/mechanism | fable-mode-profile.md:243-248,280-283 |\n| F8 | **Decision economy** — scope-frugal/process-expensive; named seam not bare TODO; never a dead control; scaffold the contract not the implementation | doctrine | fable-mode-profile.md:69-79,250-256 |\n| F9 | **Brief-as-sovereign** — read for intent; deviate from the letter only with a recorded argument; undocumented deviation is the sin; contract>spec>decisions>handoff | doctrine | fable-mode-profile.md:284-291 |\n| F10 | **Two-register voice + lexicon** — clipped-while-working / dense-at-boundaries; lead with verdict then receipts; importance via averted disaster not adjectives; no celebration/apology/flattery; pins/verify/trap/drift/load-bearing/seam/byte-identical | register/measurement | fable-mode-profile.md:420-461 |\n| F11 | **Multi-agent house rules** — LEAF disjoint-scope; git/.md ban; typed status enum (DONE/DONE_WITH_CONCERNS/NEEDS_CONTEXT/BLOCKED); two-stage spec-then-quality review; verify-personally backstop; orchestrator commits | mechanism | fable-mode-profile.md:351-360 |\n| F12 | **Reproduce-before-fix + second-break-behind-first + suspect-yourself-first** — generalize fixes so the next instance can't hide; throwaway instruments | method | fable-mode-profile.md:159-192 |\n| F13 | **Measurement integrity** — an untrustworthy number is a bug even when green; fix a gate's undercount under budget | measurement | fable-mode-profile.md:316-322 |\n| F14 | **Ration live/destructive actions** — harnesses over production; cleanup as a privacy ethic (verify the deletion) | doctrine | fable-mode-profile.md:328-372 |\n| F15 | **Worst-first triage** — named severity buckets scored by downstream consequence to a cold reader | ritual | fable-mode-profile.md:58-67 |\n\n**Root conviction (the doctrine spine):** *the expensive failures live exactly where confirmation is cheapest to skip — the gap between green and reality, between a doc and the truth — so spend lavishly to close those gaps* [SOURCE: fable-mode-profile.md:21-31]. Every F-finding descends from it.\n\n**Inherited guardrail:** \"Emulate the strengths, not the costs… scale rigor to blast radius… not a license to spawn fleets for a one-liner\" [SOURCE: fable-mode.md:11]. Named costs: verbosity at turn boundaries, a 1,323-line monotonic decision log, process outweighing small changes, autonomy outrunning operator tolerance [SOURCE: fable-mode-profile.md:491-507]. Any adoption must inherit this guardrail or it imports the cost with the strength.\n\n### 2b. From `opus-fable-mode-main/` (governor + persistence + measurement) — G1–G9\n| ID | Finding | Tag | Source |\n|----|---------|-----|--------|\n| G1 | **Opus recursion-control governor (8 rules)** — \"reason about the problem and the person, never about yourself\"; **audit depth-limit 1, never audit the audit**; start-later/stop-earlier; minimum honest qualifier; **commit with `// DECISION:`**; outcome over visible process; preserve real depth; act-don't-narrate | model-specific/doctrine | governor-block.md:1-13 |\n| G2 | **Three-layer persistence: setpoint → thermostat → measurement** — CLAUDE.md governor decays as context grows; the `UserPromptSubmit` hook re-states it every turn to defeat decay; leak_test confirms movement. **CRITICAL: the hook is subagent-BLIND — inject the governor into agent briefs separately** | mechanism | README.md:69-77; reinject.sh:8-9 |\n| G3 | **leak_test.py harness** — buckets assistant msgs by model id from JSONL logs; metrics: median words/msg, tool:text ratio, unsolicited-caveat %, \"I'll/Let me\" self-opener %; verdict = converging iff moved-toward AND closed-distance; INSUFFICIENT < 30 prose msgs | measurement | leak_test.py:28-159 |\n| G4 | **Prompt-vs-weights honesty** — a governor suppresses the disposition's *expression*, not the weights; **no capability gain**; the capability lever is task-structure (closed prompts) + multi-LLM orchestration | doctrine | README.md:6-7,79-83 |\n| G5 | **Quantified Fable signature** — median words 47→18; mean EQUAL (~99-100) so it's distribution not less; tool:text 1.41→3.91 (the token burn); result-first openers; cleanest tells = tool:text + opener style | measurement | README.md:13-21 |\n| G6 | **Extended-thinking caption test** — captions about the problem (healthy) vs about yourself (burning the budget on self-surveillance); name a self-directed thought in ≤3 words and return | model-specific/mechanism | fable-mode.md:88-102 |\n| G7 | **Reject wrong framings** — refuse a false dichotomy/bad premise and reframe; the lumpy-bit-not-armor-bit; the outward turn (ask about *their* need) | doctrine | fable-mode.md:71-84 |\n| G8 | **\"Beautiful dead end\" guardrail** — don't follow a thread to a technically-correct conclusion that no longer helps; don't overcorrect into curtness (govern the governor) | doctrine | fable-mode.md:106-117 |\n| G9 | **Anti-recursion self-check + mechanics** — one pass not a loop (did I answer or narrate difficulty; every qualifier load-bearing; made decisions or handed back; any sentence about me; 0/1 honest lump); toggle `FABLE_MODE_OFF=1`; hook timeout 5; new-session activation | mechanism | fable-mode.md:128-137; reinject.sh:11-14 |\n\n---\n\n## 3. SURFACE MAP — adjustable surfaces × read-reliability per runtime (Pillar 2)\n\nRead-reliability = probability the surface is in-context at decision time. **Decay** = loses salience as context grows. All substrate claims repo-verified [SOURCE: AGENTS.md wc=424, diff≡CLAUDE.md; ls constitutional/=16 rules+README; .claude/settings.json:14-24; ls .opencode/agents/=12; executor-config.ts present].\n\n| Surface | OpenCode | Claude | Codex | Decay | Subagent-visible | Note |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| AGENTS.md / CLAUDE.md §1-7 (setpoint) | HIGH | HIGH | HIGH | **YES** | partial | byte-synced twin; ~76-line headroom under ~500 |\n| Live `UserPromptSubmit` hook reminder (thermostat) | runtime-dep | **HIGHEST** | runtime-dep | **NO** | **NO** (main-session only) | already firing on Claude, already carries a constitutional reminder = proven ride-along |\n| Constitutional memories (16) | MED | MED-HIGH | MED | partial | via memory_search | durable auto-surface; any rule wired into the hook → HIGH |\n| Agent prompts (12 agents, 3 mirrors) | HIGH (that agent) | HIGH | HIGH | low | **YES — the only subagent surface** | 3 drifting mirrors = drift risk |\n| Skills (sk-code, sk-prompt, sk-doc, sk-git, deep-loop-workflows, system-spec-kit, system-skill-advisor) | LOW-MED | LOW-MED | LOW-MED | n/a | when invoked | high leverage, conditional |\n| Commands (deep/*, speckit/*, memory/*) | HIGH when invoked | same | same | n/a | n/a | governs one workflow only when run |\n| deep-loop runtime / executor-config / renderPromptPack / post-dispatch-validate | N/A (executable) | N/A | N/A | n/a | applies to every dispatch | where mechanisms/measurement get ENFORCED |\n| skill-advisor scoring/triggers | N/A | N/A | N/A | n/a | affects what surfaces | indirect leverage on read-reliability itself |\n\n**Conclusions:** (1) the per-turn hook is the highest-read-reliability, decay-proof, low-blast surface — but Claude-only + subagent-blind; (2) subagents are governable only via agent prompts / `renderPromptPack`; (3) AGENTS.md is high-read but decays — pair any doc governor with the thermostat; (4) constitutional rules are the durable auto-surfacing home for doctrine; (5) executor-config / post-dispatch-validate / renderPromptPack are where Tier-B/C become enforced rather than advisory. **Verified staleness candidate:** AGENTS.md cites `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/references/hooks/skill-advisor-hook.md`, which does not exist — a dead pointer in the most-read surface (exactly the rot F6 says to convert into a check).\n\n---\n\n## 4. OPTIMIZE — ranked, tiered surface×delta recommendations (Pillar 3)\n\n`Score ≈ Leverage / (Cost + Blast)`, each 1–5 (ordering aid, not precision). All NET-NEW vs round 1 unless noted. Every Tier-B/C item inherits the G4 honesty (steers efficiency, not capability) and the fable-mode.md:11 blast-radius guardrail.\n\n| # | Recommendation | Surface | Tier | Maps | Lev | Cost | Blast | Score | Dedup |\n|---|----------------|---------|------|------|-----|------|-------|-------|-------|\n| 1 | **Compact fable-5 governor on the live per-turn hook** | `user-prompt-submit.js` reminder (+ OpenCode/Codex hooks) | B | G1,G2,G5,F10 | 5 | 1 | 2 | **1.67** | net-new |\n| 2 | **Mutation-check / claim-falsifier discipline** | sk-code verification (+ optional rule) | B | F1,F3,F13 | 5 | 2 | 1 | **1.67** | net-new |\n| 3 | **Recursion-control rule + xhigh briefs** (reason-about-problem-not-yourself; depth-limit-1; caption test) | new constitutional rule + extended-thinking executor briefs | B | G1,G6,G8 | 5 | 2 | 1 | **1.67** | net-new |\n| 4 | **Engineer staleness out of artifacts** (rot→test); fix the dead hook pointer first | new rule / fold into comment-hygiene | B | F6,F4,F13 | 4 | 2 | 2 | **1.00** | partial |\n| 5 | **Inject governor into agent prompts / renderPromptPack** (subagent surface) | agent prompts + deep-loop render | B | G2,G1,G6 | 5 | 3 | 3 | **0.83** | net-new (needs sync) |\n| 6 | **Small doctrine-spine line in AGENTS.md §1** (root conviction + register + letter-vs-intent), paired with #1 | AGENTS.md/CLAUDE.md §1 | A | spine,F8,F9,F10 | 3 | 1 | 2 | **1.00** | net-new (NOT a restate of round-1 subsection) |\n| 7 | **leak_test-style behavioral metric** | `/doctor` route or `deep:*-benchmark` dimension | C | G3,G5,F13 | 4 | 4 | 1 | **0.80** | net-new |\n| 8 | **Scar-tissue + cold-successor handoff discipline** | handover.md + _memory.continuity | A/B | F4,F5 | 3 | 2 | 1 | **1.00** | net-new |\n| 9 | **Verification ladder w/ named blind spots** | sk-code + deep-review | B | F2 | 3 | 1 | 1 | **1.50** | partial |\n| 10 | **Adversarial-review schema + machine-checkable evidence contract** | @orchestrate/@deep-review prompts + post-dispatch-validate | B | F3,F11,F15,F5 | 5 | 5 | 4 | **0.56** | = round-1 carried follow-up (dedicated packet) |\n| 11 | **Decision-economy + fail-closed-by-construction doctrine** | sk-code doctrine (+ optional rule) | A | F7,F8 | 3 | 1 | 1 | **1.50** | net-new |\n| 12 | **Fail-loud on model mismatch in executor-audit** | executor-audit / dispatch | B | F7,F13,G4 | 4 | 3 | 3 | hardening | = round-1 carried follow-up (codex SIGKILL/silent-gpt-5; dedicated packet) |\n\n**Land-first cluster (#1–#3):** high-leverage, low-cost, low-blast, and squarely on \"efficiency.\" **Durable/cheap (#4, #6, #8, #9, #11).** **High-value-real-cost (#5, #7).** **Dedicated packets (#10, #12)** — both are the carried round-1 follow-ups: highest leverage, highest cost, and structural (TypeScript runtime + schema work), not surgical drops.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Carried round-1 follow-ups — re-assessed\n\n- **Machine-checkable evidence contract (= rec #10): STILL OPEN.** Grep for its named fields (`claim_class`, `would_confirm`, `gate_delta`, `scope_state`, `child_result_verified`, \"evidence contract\") across `deep-loop-runtime` + `system-spec-kit/references` → zero hits [SOURCE: grep no-match]. The attachment point exists (`validateIterationOutputs` / post-dispatch-validate; `agent-io-contract.md`); the schema does not. Confirms round-1's deferral [SOURCE: 149/001 implementation-summary.md:130].\n- **codex SIGKILL / silent gpt-5 fallback (= rec #12): STILL OPEN structurally; mitigated operationally this round.** No model-verification / fail-loud / SIGKILL handling in the runtime — only generic env `fallback` + a \"corrupt lines silently dropped\" note [SOURCE: grep no-match over deep-loop-runtime/scripts + deep-research/scripts]. The 002 spec guards it by process (pre-flight smoke + verify-model-in-logs) [SOURCE: 002 spec.md:99-128], not by a runtime fix. Rec #12 makes it structural: compare requested vs actual model in the executor audit and emit `error`/`blocked_stop` rather than silently substitute.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Eliminated Alternatives (negative knowledge — primary output)\n\n| Approach | Reason eliminated | Evidence | Iter |\n|----------|-------------------|----------|------|\n| Re-recommending round-1's shipped set (Operating Discipline subsection, 2 rules, the fold, sk-code line) | Out of scope per 002 spec | 149/001 implementation-summary.md:56-81 | 1 |\n| Importing Fable's em-dash habit / monotonic decision-log bloat | Fable's own failure modes (costs), not techniques | fable-mode-profile.md:491-507 | 1 |\n| Verbatim copy of `governor-block.md` into our CLAUDE.md | Byte-synced twin set already near the ~500-line budget; verbatim paste bloats the most-read surface | governor-block.md:1-13; 149/001 changelog.md:22 | 2 |\n| Porting `leak_test.py` as-is | Targets `claude-*` ids + `~/.claude/projects` layout; multi-runtime port needs runtime-aware bucketing | leak_test.py:38-44 | 2 |\n| AGENTS.md/CLAUDE.md as the *sole* home for a persistent governor | Setpoint decays (G2); doc-only repeats round-1's advisory-only weakness — must pair with the thermostat | opus README.md:69-77 | 3 |\n| Hand-editing the 3 agent mirrors as a first move without a sync mechanism | 3-runtime-mirror drift risk | 149/001 implementation-summary.md:101 | 3 |\n| Adopting F14 (ration live actions / cleanup-as-privacy) as a rec | Low relevance; no shared production box; partially covered by name-the-rollback | iteration-001.md F14 | 4 |\n| Standalone F12 / G7 / G8 recs | F12 covered by round-1 finding-is-a-hypothesis; G7/G8 folded into rec #3's governor guardrails | iteration-004.md | 4 |\n| Treating codex SIGKILL as fixed because the 002 pre-flight smoke passed | Smoke is an operational guard for this round; the runtime still lacks model-mismatch fail-loud | grep no-hits; 002 spec.md:125-128 | 5 |\n\n---\n\n## 7. Open questions & gaps (for the cross-lineage merge)\n\n**Gaps in this lineage:**\n1. OpenCode/Codex per-turn-hook read-reliability unverified (rated \"runtime-dep\"; only the Claude hook wiring was opened directly).\n2. Numeric leverage/(cost+blast) scores are deliberately coarse; #5/#10/#12 cost-blast are estimates an implementation packet must firm up.\n3. leak_test multi-runtime port unscoped (metric definitions portable; per-runtime log-location/model-id mapping not specified).\n4. `leak_test.py` not run (needs real transcripts + out of research-only scope) — G5 signature cited from the source corpus, not reproduced on this repo.\n\n**Merge questions:**\n- **Q-merge-1:** does codex-xhigh confirm/contradict the read-reliability matrix (OpenCode/Codex hook + AGENTS.md decay)?\n- **Q-merge-2:** do both lineages independently rank the same top cluster (governor-on-hook / mutation-check / recursion-control)?\n- **Q-merge-3:** did either lineage surface a surface×delta this one missed? Union, then re-dedup vs round 1.\n- **Q-merge-4:** tier-A budget check — do the AGENTS.md/CLAUDE.md twins stay under ~500 lines after a doctrine-spine addition (#6)?\n\n---\n\n## 8. References\n\n- `external/fable-mode-main/fable-mode-profile.md`, `fable-mode.md`, `README.md`\n- `external/opus-fable-mode-main/governor-block.md`, `fable-mode.md`, `reinject.sh`, `leak_test.py`, `install/settings-hook-snippet.json`, `README.md`\n- `external/Fable5.md` (round-1 doctrine baseline; dedup reference)\n- `149/001-initial-refinement/implementation-summary.md`, `changelog.md` (round-1 shipped set + carried follow-ups)\n- Repo-verified surfaces: `AGENTS.md`/`CLAUDE.md`; `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/constitutional/*` (16 rules); `.claude/settings.json` (UserPromptSubmit hook); `.opencode/agents/*` (12 agents); `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/lib/deep-loop/executor-config.ts`\n- This lineage's iterations: `iterations/iteration-001.md` … `iteration-005.md`; state in `deep-research-state.jsonl`; registry in `deep-research-findings-registry.json`\n- (resource-map.md not present at init; coverage gate skipped)","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":148,"totalLines":148,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/149-operate-like-fable-5/002-fable-mode-efficiency-research/research/lineages/opus-account2/research.md","time":{"start":1781519212540,"end":1781519212544}},"id":"prt_ecad1dd27001Oa4oAvjcEg5cvy","sessionID":"ses_1352f6392ffeYuDqFBXc7h0kg7","messageID":"msg_ecad1c871001ZQ7e0gXgC7KLzR"}}
